{"title_page": "Willie Carlin", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name      = Willie Carlin\n| image = \n| fullname = William Carlin<ref>{{Hugman|3093|accessdate=3 November 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1940|10|6|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Liverpool]], England\n| height = {{height|ft=5|in=4}}<ref name=LFCprofile>{{cite web |url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/history/past-players/willie-carlin |title=Willie Carlin |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref>\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = 1956\u20131958\n| youthclubs1 = [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]\n| years1 = 1958\u20131962\n| clubs1 = [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]\n| caps1  = 1\n| goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 1962\u20131964\n| clubs2 = [[Halifax Town A.F.C.|Halifax Town]]\n| caps2  = 95\n| goals2 = 32\n| years3 = 1964\u20131967\n| clubs3 = [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]]\n| caps3  = 93\n| goals3 = 21\n| years4 = 1967\u20131968\n| clubs4 = [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]\n| caps4  = 36\n| goals4 = 3\n| years5 = 1968\u20131970\n| clubs5 = [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]]\n| caps5  = 89\n| goals5 = 14\n| years6 = 1970\u20131971\n| clubs6 = [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]]\n| caps6  = 31\n| goals6 = 1\n| years7 = 1971\u20131973\n| clubs7 = [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]]\n| caps7  = 60\n| goals7 = 2\n| years8 = 1973\u20131974\n| clubs8 = [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]]\n| caps8  = 22\n| goals8 = 1\n|totalcaps = \n|totalgoals = \n}}\n'''William Carlin''' (born 6 October 1940) is an English former professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a central midfielder. During his career, he made over 400 appearances in the [[Football League]], scoring 74 times.<ref name=ATZ>{{Cite web |url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/player/williecarlin.html |title=Willie Carlin |website=Post War English & Scottish Football League A\u2013Z Player's Database |publisher=Neil Brown |accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref> He began his career with his hometown club [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], making one appearance for the club in 1959,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lfchistory.net/Players/Player/GamesPerSeason/460-1 |title=List of appearances in 1959\u20131960 by Willie Carlin |publisher=LFCHistory |accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref> before joining [[Halifax Town A.F.C.|Halifax Town]] in 1962.<ref name=LFCprofile/> He joined [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]] in 1964 and went on to make over 100 appearances in all competitions for the club, helping them win the [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] in 1965.\n\nAfter one season with [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]], Carlin was persuaded to join [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] by manager [[Brian Clough]] and went on to play a pivotal role in the ''Rams'' [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] title winning side during the 1968\u201369 season and played one season in the First Division for the club. He later finished his career with spells at [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]], [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] and [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]].<ref name=ATZ/> Standing at five foot and four inches and weighing less than 10 stone, Carlin became well known for his diminutive size and his tenacity on the pitch,<ref name=Newspaper>{{cite web |url=http://www.lfchistory.net/images/newspapers/ian.beardsley/carlin-career.jpg |title=Willie Carlin newspaper interview |publisher=LFCHistory (source) |accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=Cards>{{cite web |url=http://cards.littleoak.com.au/player_pages/015_willie_carlin.html |title=Willie Carlin |publisher=Nigel's Webspace \u2013 Galleries of English Football Cards 1965/66 \u2013 1979/80  |accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref> being described by Brian Clough as \"a belligerent, aggressive little Scouser\".<ref name=Clough>{{cite book |title=Brian Clough: Nobody Ever Says Thank You |publisher=Hachette UK |author=Jonathan Wilson |isbn=978-0753828717}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nHaving represented England at schoolboy level,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://playupliverpool.com/1956/05/16/school-star-willie-carlin/ |title=School star Willie Carlin |publisher=The Daily Mirror |date=16 May 1956 |accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref> Carlin began at his hometown club, and the club he supported,<ref name=Newspaper/> [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], joining the side in 1956 before signing a professional contract two years later in May 1958.<ref name=LFCHprofile>{{cite web |url=http://www.lfchistory.net/Players/Player/Profile/460 |title=Willie Carlin |publisher=LFCHistory |accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref> The following season, Carlin was handed his professional debut for the club in the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] at the age of 19, playing in a 2\u20132 draw with [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] on 10 October 1959.<ref name=LFCHprofile/> He remained at [[Anfield]] until 1962 but did not make any further appearances for the club and was sold to [[Football League Third Division|Division Three]] side [[Halifax Town A.F.C.|Halifax Town]] in August 1962 for a fee of \u00a31,500.<ref name=Newspaper/> At Halifax, Carlin was relegated for the first time in his career during his first season at the club, dropping into the [[Football League Fourth Division|Fourth Division]],<ref name=LFCHprofile/> but made his name as a midfield schemer before joining [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]] in 1964 for a fee of \u00a310,000.<ref name=Newspaper/> After initially clashing with coach [[Dick Young (footballer)|Dick Young]], Carlin soon settled with the ''Cumbrians'' and later credited Young with \"making a real man of me\".<ref name=Newspaper/>\n\nHe helped Carlisle win promotion to the Second Division, despite suffering a broken leg during the 1965\u201366 season,<ref name=Cards/> before joining [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] in 1967 for \u00a340,000, signing a five-year contract with the ''Blades'', where he spent one season before attracting the interest of [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]], whose manager [[Brian Clough]] had followed his progress for several years and had previously attempted to buy Carlin during his time with Carlisle but had been charged by the [[Football Association]] after making an illegal approach to him.<ref name=Newspaper/> When Carlisle had sold Carlin to Sheffield United, Clough had furiously stated \"Carlisle have sold a player for a certain fee when [...] we were prepared to top it\".<ref name=Clough/> Carlin initially refused to meet Clough to discuss a transfer but was convinced to meet Clough by Sheffield United manager [[Arthur Rowley]], who told Carling that it would be \"rude\" to ignore the meeting. Carlin eventually accepted the move after his wife Marie declared her wish to move away from [[Sheffield]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nottinghampost.com/clough-taylor-transformed-fortunes-derby-county/story-12171402-detail/story.html |title=How Clough and Taylor transformed the fortunes of Derby County |publisher=Nottingham Post |date=8 October 2010 |accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref> Carlin travelled to Derby the following day and the transfer was completed for a fee of \u00a363,000.<ref name=Newspaper/> Rowley had been unimpressed with Carlin during his time in charge and believed he had \"got one over\" on Clough having described Carlin as \"an over-aggressive and slow midfielder who couldn't keep his mouth shut\".<ref name=Clough/>\n\nCarlin made his debut for the ''Rams'' in a 2\u20132 draw with [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]], scoring one of his side's goals.<ref name=Clough/> After winning another promotion, scoring the goal that sealed promotion in the 1968\u201369 season,<ref name=Newspaper/> Carlin helped Derby establish themselves as a force in the First Division under [[Brian Clough]]. After spells playing for [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] and [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]], he moved to [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] in November 1973, being brought in by his former Leicester boss [[Frank O'Farrell]]. He made his debut during a 1\u20130 victory over [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] and was instrumental in helping the club avoid relegation, his final professional appearance coming in the final game of the season against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] that decided which of the two sides would be relegated,<ref name=Cards/> before deciding to retire at the end of the season.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Who's Who of Cardiff City | first = Dean | last = Hayes | publisher = Breedon Books | year = 2006 | p=33\u201334 | location=Derby | isbn= 1-85983-462-0}}</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nAfter retiring from football, Carlin ran a bar in [[Majorca]], Spain.<ref name=Cards/> He retired to the area of [[Allestree]] in [[Derbyshire]]. In April 2011, Carlin's house was targeted by burglars who broke into his home using a spade and stole his winners medal from the 1968\u201369 season with Derby County and the gold commemorative bracelet that was awarded to each player.<ref name=Stolen>{{cite web |url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/willie-s-rams-medal-snatched-thieves/story-11602786-detail/story.html |title=Willie's Rams medal snatched by thieves |publisher=Derby Telegraph |date=29 April 2011 |accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-13810129 |title=Ex-Derby County player Willie Carlin has medal stolen |publisher=BBC News |date=17 June 2011 |accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n'''Carlisle United'''\n*'''[[Football League Third Division]]''' winner: 1964\u201365<ref name=Newspaper/>\n\n'''Derby County'''\n*'''[[Football League Second Division]]''' winner: 1968\u201369<ref name=Stolen/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carlin, Willie}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Liverpool F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Halifax Town A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Carlisle United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sheffield United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Derby County F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Leicester City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Notts County F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Cardiff City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Liverpool]]\n[[Category:People from Allestree]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name      = Willie Carlin\n| image = \n| fullname = William Carlin<ref>{{Hugman|3093|accessdate=3 November 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1940|10|6|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Liverpool]], England\n| height = {{height|ft=5|in=4}}<ref name=LFCprofile>{{cite web |url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/history/past-players/willie-carlin |title=Willie Carlin |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref>\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = 1956\u20131958\n| youthclubs1 = [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]\n| years1 = 1958\u20131962\n| clubs1 = [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]\n| caps1  = 1\n| goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 1962\u20131964\n| clubs2 = [[Halifax Town A.F.C.|Halifax Town]]\n| caps2  = 95\n| goals2 = 32\n| years3 = 1964\u20131967\n| clubs3 = [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]]\n| caps3  = 93\n| goals3 = 21\n| years4 = 1967\u20131968\n| clubs4 = [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]\n| caps4  = 36\n| goals4 = 3\n| years5 = 1968\u20131970\n| clubs5 = [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]]\n| caps5  = 89\n| goals5 = 14\n| years6 = 1970\u20131971\n| clubs6 = [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]]\n| caps6  = 31\n| goals6 = 1\n| years7 = 1971\u20131973\n| clubs7 = [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]]\n| caps7  = 60\n| goals7 = 2\n| years8 = 1973\u20131974\n| clubs8 = [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]]\n| caps8  = 22\n| goals8 = 1\n|totalcaps = \n|totalgoals = \n}}\n'''William Carlin''' (born 6 October 1940) is an English former professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a central midfielder. During his career, he made over 400 appearances in the [[Football League]], scoring 74 times.<ref name=ATZ>{{Cite web |url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/player/williecarlin.html |title=Willie Carlin |website=Post War English & Scottish Football League A\u2013Z Player's Database |publisher=Neil Brown |accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref> He began his career with his hometown club [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], making one appearance for the club in 1959,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lfchistory.net/Players/Player/GamesPerSeason/460-1 |title=List of appearances in 1959\u20131960 by Willie Carlin |publisher=LFCHistory |accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref> before joining [[Halifax Town A.F.C.|Halifax Town]] in 1962.<ref name=LFCprofile/> He joined [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]] in 1964 and went on to make over 100 appearances in all competitions for the club, helping them win the [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] in 1965.\n\nAfter one season with [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]], Carlin was persuaded to join [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] by manager [[Brian Clough]] and went on to play a pivotal role in the ''Rams'' [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] title winning side during the 1968\u201369 season and played one season in the First Division for the club. He later finished his career with spells at [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]], [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] and [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]].<ref name=ATZ/> Standing at five foot and four inches and weighing less than 10 stone, Carlin became well known for his diminutive size and his tenacity on the pitch,<ref name=Newspaper>{{cite web |url=http://www.lfchistory.net/images/newspapers/ian.beardsley/carlin-career.jpg |title=Willie Carlin newspaper interview |publisher=LFCHistory (source) |accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=Cards>{{cite web |url=http://cards.littleoak.com.au/player_pages/015_willie_carlin.html |title=Willie Carlin |publisher=Nigel's Webspace \u2013 Galleries of English Football Cards 1965/66 \u2013 1979/80  |accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref> being described by Brian Clough as \"a belligerent, aggressive little Scouser\".<ref name=Clough>{{cite book |title=Brian Clough: Nobody Ever Says Thank You |publisher=Hachette UK |author=Jonathan Wilson |isbn=978-0753828717}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nHaving represented England at schoolboy level,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://playupliverpool.com/1956/05/16/school-star-willie-carlin/ |title=School star Willie Carlin |publisher=The Daily Mirror |date=16 May 1956 |accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref> Carlin began at his hometown club, and the club he supported,<ref name=Newspaper/> [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], joining the side in 1956 before signing a professional contract two years later in May 1958.<ref name=LFCHprofile>{{cite web |url=http://www.lfchistory.net/Players/Player/Profile/460 |title=Willie Carlin |publisher=LFCHistory |accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref> The following season, Carlin was handed his professional debut for the club in the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] at the age of 19, playing in a 2\u20132 draw with [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] on 10 October 1959.<ref name=LFCHprofile/> He remained at [[Anfield]] until 1962 but did not make any further appearances for the club and was sold to [[Football League Third Division|Division Three]] side [[Halifax Town A.F.C.|Halifax Town]] in August 1962 for a fee of \u00a31,500.<ref name=Newspaper/> At Halifax, Carlin was relegated for the first time in his career during his first season at the club, dropping into the [[Football League Fourth Division|Fourth Division]],<ref name=LFCHprofile/> but made his name as a midfield schemer before joining [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]] in 1964 for a fee of \u00a310,000.<ref name=Newspaper/> After initially clashing with coach [[Dick Young (footballer)|Dick Young]], Carlin soon settled with the ''Cumbrians'' and later credited Young with \"making a real man of me\".<ref name=Newspaper/>\n\nHe helped Carlisle win promotion to the Second Division, despite suffering a broken leg during the 1965\u201366 season,<ref name=Cards/> before joining [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] in 1967 for \u00a340,000, signing a five-year contract with the ''Blades'', where he spent one season before attracting the interest of [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]], whose manager [[Brian Clough]] had followed his progress for several years and had previously attempted to buy Carlin during his time with Carlisle but had been charged by the [[Football Association]] after making an illegal approach to him.<ref name=Newspaper/> When Carlisle had sold Carlin to Sheffield United, Clough had furiously stated \"Carlisle have sold a player for a certain fee when [...] we were prepared to top it\".<ref name=Clough/> Carlin initially refused to meet Clough to discuss a transfer but was convinced to meet Clough by Sheffield United manager [[Arthur Rowley]], who told Carling that it would be \"rude\" to ignore the meeting. Carlin eventually accepted the move after his wife Marie declared her wish to move away from [[Sheffield]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nottinghampost.com/clough-taylor-transformed-fortunes-derby-county/story-12171402-detail/story.html |title=How Clough and Taylor transformed the fortunes of Derby County |publisher=Nottingham Post |date=8 October 2010 |accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref> Carlin travelled to Derby the following day and the transfer was completed for a fee of \u00a363,000.<ref name=Newspaper/> Rowley had been unimpressed with Carlin during his time in charge and believed he had \"got one over\" on Clough having described Carlin as \"an over-aggressive and slow midfielder who couldn't keep his mouth shut\".<ref name=Clough/>\n\nCarlin made his debut for the ''Rams'' in a 2\u20132 draw with [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]], scoring one of his side's goals.<ref name=Clough/> After winning another promotion, scoring the goal that sealed promotion in the 1968\u201369 season,<ref name=Newspaper/> Carlin helped Derby establish themselves as a force in the First Division under [[Brian Clough]]. After spells playing for [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] and [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]], he moved to [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] in November 1973, being brought in by his former Leicester boss [[Frank O'Farrell]]. He made his debut during a 1\u20130 victory over [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] and was instrumental in helping the club avoid relegation, his final professional appearance coming in the final game of the season against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] that decided which of the two sides would be relegated,<ref name=Cards/> before deciding to retire at the end of the season.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Who's Who of Cardiff City | first = Dean | last = Hayes | publisher = Breedon Books | year = 2006 | p=33\u201334 | location=Derby | isbn= 1-85983-462-0}}</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nAfter retiring from football, Carlin ran a bar in [[Majorca]], Spain.<ref name=Cards/> He retired to the area of [[Allestree]] in [[Derbyshire]]. In April 2011, Carlin's house was targeted by burglars who broke into his home using a spade and stole his winners medal from the 1968\u201369 season with Derby County and the gold commemorative bracelet that was awarded to each player.<ref name=Stolen>{{cite web |url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/willie-s-rams-medal-snatched-thieves/story-11602786-detail/story.html |title=Willie's Rams medal snatched by thieves |publisher=Derby Telegraph |date=29 April 2011 |accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-13810129 |title=Ex-Derby County player Willie Carlin has medal stolen |publisher=BBC News |date=17 June 2011 |accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n'''Carlisle United'''\n*'''[[Football League Third Division]]''' winner: 1964\u201365<ref name=Newspaper/>\n\n'''Derby County'''\n*'''[[Football League Second Division]]''' winner: 1968\u201369<ref name=Stolen/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carlin, Willie}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Liverpool F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Halifax Town A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Carlisle United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sheffield United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Derby County F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Leicester City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Notts County F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Cardiff City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Liverpool]]\n[[Category:People from Allestree]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Willie_Carlin"}
{"title_page": "Willie Campbell (footballer)", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{unreferenced|date=May 2009}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Willie Campbell\n| fullname =\n| birth_date = 1900\n| birth_place = [[Dunfermline]], Scotland\n| death_date = \n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1 =   \n| youthclubs1 =   \n|  years1 =  \n| years2 =  \n| years3 =   1927\u20131929  \n| years4 =\n|  clubs1 =   [[Cowdenbeath F.C.|Cowdenbeath]]  \n| clubs2 =   [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa Athletic]]  \n| clubs3 =   [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]]  \n| clubs4 =   [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]\n| caps1 =   \n| caps2 =  \n| caps3 =   3   \n| caps4 =  \n| goals1 = \n| goals2 =  \n| goals3 =  0  \n| goals4 = \n}}\n\n'''William R. Campbell''' (born 1900) was a Scottish professional [[association football|footballer]] who played for [[Cowdenbeath F.C.|Cowdenbeath]], [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa Athletic]], [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] &  [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]. He was born in [[Dunfermline]].\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Campbell, Willie}}\n[[Category:1900 births]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:Alloa Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Cowdenbeath F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Huddersfield Town A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Manchester City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Dunfermline]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-footy-defender-1900s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{unreferenced|date=May 2009}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Willie Campbell\n| fullname = William R. Campbell\n| birth_date = 1900\n| birth_place = [[Dunfermline]], [[Scotland]]\n| death_date = \n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1 =   \n| youthclubs1 =   \n|  years1 =   ?  \n| years2 =   ?  \n| years3 =   1927\u20131929  \n| years4 =   ?\n|  clubs1 =   [[Cowdenbeath F.C.|Cowdenbeath]]  \n| clubs2 =   [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa Athletic]]  \n| clubs3 =   [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]]  \n| clubs4 =   [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]\n| caps1 =    ?   \n| caps2 =   ?   \n| caps3 =   3   \n| caps4 =   ?  \n| goals1 =  ?  \n| goals2 =  ?  \n| goals3 =  0  \n| goals4 =  ? \n}}\n\n'''William R. \"Willie\" Campbell''' (born 1900) was a [[Scotland|Scottish]] [[professional]] [[association football|footballer]] who played for [[Cowdenbeath F.C.|Cowdenbeath]], [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa Athletic]], [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] &  [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]. He was born in [[Dunfermline]].\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Campbell, Willie}}\n[[Category:1900 births]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:Alloa Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Cowdenbeath F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Huddersfield Town A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Manchester City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Dunfermline]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-footy-defender-1900s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Willie_Campbell_(footballer)"}
{"title_page": "2000 Toronto Blue Jays season", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox MLB yearly\n| name = Toronto Blue Jays\n| season = 2000\n| misc =\n| logo =\n| current league = American League\n| y1 = 1977\n| division = [[American League East|East Division]]\n| y2 = 1977\n| Uniform logo =\n| ballpark = [[SkyDome]]\n| y4 = 1989\n| city = [[Toronto]]\n| y5 = 1977\n| record         = 83\u201379 (.512)\n| divisional place = 3rd\n| owners = [[Rogers Communications]], [[Interbrew]]\n| general managers = [[Gord Ash]]\n| managers = [[Jim Fregosi]]\n| television = [[CBC Television]]<br>([[Brian Williams (sportscaster)|Brian Williams]], [[Rich Waltz]], [[John Cerutti]])<br>[[The Sports Network]]<br>([[Dan Shulman]], [[Buck Martinez]])<br>[[Rogers Sportsnet|CTV Sportsnet]]<br>([[Rod Black]], [[Joe Carter]])\n| radio = [[CHUM (AM)]]<br>([[Jerry Howarth]], [[Tom Cheek]], [[Gary Matthews]])\n|}}\nThe '''2000 [[Toronto Blue Jays]]''' season was the franchise's 24th season of [[Major League Baseball]]. It resulted in the Blue Jays finishing third in the [[American League]] East with a record of 83 wins and 79 losses. It is the team's first season with new mascots [[Toronto Blue Jays mascots|Ace]] and [[Toronto Blue Jays mascots|Diamond]].\n\n==Offseason==\n* November 8, 1999: [[Ra\u00fal Mondes\u00ed]] was traded by the Los Angeles Dodgers with Pedro Borb\u00f3n to the Toronto Blue Jays for Shawn Green and Jorge Nunez (minors).<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/m/mondera01.shtml Ra\u00fal Mondes\u00ed Statistics] Baseball-Reference.com</ref>\n*November 11, 1999: Paul Spoljaric was traded by the Toronto Blue Jays with Pat Hentgen to the St. Louis Cardinals for Alberto Castillo, Matt DeWitt, and Lance Painter.<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/s/spoljpa01.shtml Paul Spoljaric Statistics] Baseball-Reference.com</ref>\nDecember 13, 1999: DeWayne Wise was drafted by the Toronto Blue Jays from the Cincinnati Reds in the 1999 rule 5 draft.<ref>https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/w/wisede01.shtml</ref>\n\n==Regular season==\n\n===Season standings===\n{{2000 AL East standings|highlight=Toronto Blue Jays}}\n\n===Record vs. opponents===\n{{2000 AL Record vs. opponents|team=TOR}}\n\n===Notable transactions===\nJuly 19, 2000: [[Esteban Loaiza]] was traded by the Texas Rangers to the Toronto Blue Jays for Darwin Cubill\u00e1n and Michael Young.<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/l/loaizes01.shtml Esteban Loaiza Statistics] Baseball-Reference.com</ref>\n*July 26, 2000: [[Rob Ducey]] was traded by the Philadelphia Phillies to the Toronto Blue Jays for a player to be named later. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/d/duceyro01.shtml |title= Rob Ducey: Career Statistics |publisher= Baseball Reference| accessdate= 14 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2000 Draft picks===\n''Source'' <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/draft/index.cgi?team_ID=TOR&year_ID=2000&draft_type=junreg&query_type=franch_year|title=Feature: 2000 Free Agent Draft Pick Compensation |work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]] |accessdate=September 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2001 Major League Baseball draft|2002 MLB draft]] was held in June 2001.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%; text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#005ac0;\" color:white;\"| <span style=\"color:white;\">Round</span>\n! style=\"background:#005ac0;\" color:white;\"| <span style=\"color:white;\">Pick</span>\n! style=\"background:#005ac0;\" color:white;\"| <span style=\"color:white;\">Player</span>\n! style=\"background:#005ac0;\" color:white;\"| <span style=\"color:white;\">Position</span>\n! style=\"background:#005ac0;\" color:white;\"| <span style=\"color:white;\">College/School</span>\n! style=\"background:#005ac0;\" color:white;\"| <span style=\"color:white;\">Nationality</span>\n|-\n!width=\"65\"|\n!width=\"45\"|\n! style=\"width:150px;\"|\n!width=\"60\"|\n! style=\"width:250px;\"|\n! style=\"width:100px;\"|\n|-\n| 1\n| 18\