{"title_page": "2nd New York Volunteer Cavalry Regiment", "text_new": "{{About|the regiment nicknamed the Harris Light|the unit nicknamed the Northern Black Horse also designated by New York state authority as the 2nd Cavalry|7th Regiment New York Volunteer Cavalry}}{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name =2nd Regiment New York Volunteer Cavalry\n| image = \n| dates = October 8, 1861\u2013June 5, 1865\n| country = {{flag|United States of America|1863}}\n| allegiance = [[Union (Civil War)|Union]]\n| branch = [[Union Army]]\n| type = [[Cavalry in the American Civil War|Cavalry]]\n| nickname = Harris Light Cavalry\n| battles = [[American Civil War]]\n| notable_commanders = Col. [[Judson Kilpatrick]]<br />Col. [[Henry Eugene Davies]]<br />Col. [[Alanson M. Randol]]\n}}\n\n[[File:Private Thomas Dennis of Co. G, 2nd New York Cavalry Regiment in uniform with American flag LOC ppmsca.52246.jpg|thumb|right|Private Thomas Dennis of Co. G, 2nd New York Cavalry Regiment. From the Liljenquist Family Collection of Civil War Photographs, Prints and Photographs Division, [[Library of Congress]]]]\n\nThe '''2nd New York Volunteer Cavalry Regiment''' (Officially \"2nd Regiment New York Volunteer Cavalry\") was a unit of the [[Union Army]] during the [[American Civil War]].\n\n==History==\nColonel J. Mansfield Davies was authorized by the [[War Department (US)|War Department]] to recruit the regiment, unofficially known as the Harris Light Cavalry, on July, 25, 1861. Its twelve companies were recruited as follows: \n\n* Company A at New York City, [[Hartford, Connecticut]], and [[Newton, New Jersey]], \n* Company B at Newton and [[Deckertown|Deckertown, New Jersey]], \n* Companies C and D \u2013 known as the Connecticut Squadron \u2013 at Hartford, \n*Company E at New York City, [[Troy, New York|Troy]], [[Fort Edward (town), New York|Fort Edward]], and [[Cambridge, New York]],\n* Company F at [[Covington, Indiana]], [[Fairfield, Vermont]], Troy, and [[Richfield Springs, New York]], \n* Company G at New York City, [[Newburgh, New York|Newburgh]], and Fort Edward, \n* Company H at [[Chambersburg, Indiana]], I at [[Lafayette, Indiana]], \n* Company K at [[Scranton, Pennsylvania]], [[Hampton, New Jersey|Hampton]], [[Newark, New Jersey|Newark]], and [[Rockaway, New Jersey]], New York City, Troy, and Richfield Springs, \n* Company L at New York City, [[Hudson, New York|Hudson]], Troy, [[Fort Ann, New York|Fort Ann]], Fort Edward and [[Litchfield, New York|Litchfield]], and\n* Company M at New York City, Newburgh, [[Plattsburgh (city), New York|Plattsburgh]] and [[Port Henry, New York|Port Henry]].{{Sfn|Phisterer|1912|p=751}}\n\nThe regiment was organized at [[Scarsdale, New York]], where it was mustered into Federal service for a term of three years between August 9 and October 8, 1861. The War Department designated the regiment as the 7th United States Cavalry on October 26, but it was transferred to New York state service as the 2nd New York Volunteer Cavalry,{{Sfn|Phisterer|1912|p=751}} as Congress had not provided for a seventh [[Regular Army (United States)|Regular Army]] cavalry regiment.{{Sfn|Dyer|1908|p=1370}}\n\nAfter leaving New York during September and October, the regiment served with [[Irvin McDowell|McDowell]]'s Division of the [[Army of the Potomac]] from the latter month,  on duty in the defenses of [[Washington, D.C.|Washington, D.C]].{{Sfn|Dyer|1908|p=1370}} It was transferred to the Third Division of the [[I Corps (Union Army)|First Corps]] of the Army of the Potomac in March 1862, and in May briefly became part of [[Rufus King (general)|King]]'s Division of the [[Department of the Rappahannock]]. The 2nd New York Volunteer Cavalry formed part of the Cavalry Brigade of the Second Division of the Third Corps of the [[Army of Virginia]] (temporarily redesignated from the First Corps) from June. It was transferred to [[George D. Bayard|Bayard]]'s Cavalry Brigade of the Army of the Potomac in September, while Companies A, B, I, and K were detached to the Third Division of the First Corps during September and October. J. Mansfield Davies resigned on December 6, and was replaced as colonel by regimental Lieutenant Colonel [[Judson Kilpatrick]].{{Sfn|Phisterer|1912|p=754}}<ref>https://catalog.archives.gov/id/76062574</ref> After Bayard's death, the brigade that included the regiment came under the command of Brigadier General [[David McMurtrie Gregg]] on December 15.{{Sfn|Phisterer|1912|p=751}}\n[[File:2nd-NY-Cav-Monument.jpg|thumb|Monument to the 2nd New York Cavalry at Gettysburg]]\nThe 2nd New York was assigned to the First Brigade of the Third Division of the [[Cavalry Corps (Union Army)|Cavalry Corps]] of the Army of the Potomac on February 11, 1863, detaching a battalion to the First Brigade of the First Division of the [[IV Corps (Union Army)|Fourth Corps]] for service on the [[Virginia Peninsula]] between May and July. During [[Stoneman's 1863 raid]], the regiment was sent against Richmond and the [[Chickahominy River|Chickahominy]] railroad bridges.{{Sfn|Greene|2009|p=83}} After Kilpatrick was promoted to brigadier general on June 13, Lieutenant Colonel [[Henry Eugene Davies|Henry E. Davies]] was promoted to colonel in his stead three days later.{{Sfn|Phisterer|1912|p=754}} The regiment was transferred to the Second Brigade of the Second Division of the cavalry of the Army of the Potomac on June 14.{{Sfn|Phisterer|1912|p=751}} \n\nIt again returned to the First Brigade of the Third Division of the Cavalry Corps on August 12. Davies was promoted to brigadier general on September 16, leaving regimental Lieutenant Colonel Otto Harhaus, promoted to colonel on April 1, 1864, in command.{{Sfn|Phisterer|1912|p=754}} During the [[Wilson\u2013Kautz Raid]], on June 23, 1864, the regiment tore up tracks on the [[Southside Railroad (Virginia)|South Side Railroad]] at Ford's Depot.{{Sfn|Greene|2018|p=574n53}} When the regimental term of service expired, those who had served out their terms were discharged and on August 29, the recruits and reenlisted veterans of the 2nd New York Volunteer Cavalry was consolidated into a four-company battalion including Companies A, B, C, and D that continued in service. Eight new companies, recruited for a one year term of service, expanded the 2nd New York Cavalry to a regiment again by their addition in September and October.{{Sfn|Phisterer|1912|p=751}} \n\nThe eight new companies were recruited as follows:\n\n*Company E \u2013 known as the Ticonderoga Cavalry Company \u2013 at Plattsburgh and [[Ticonderoga, New York|Ticonderoga]],\n*Company F at [[Elmira, New York|Elmira]] and [[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]],\n*Companies G and H at [[Manlius, New York|Manlius]], [[Rochester, New York|Rochester]], [[Elbridge, New York|Elbridge]], [[Onondaga, New York|Onondaga]], Syracuse, [[Cicero, New York|Cicero]], [[Pompey, New York|Pompey]], [[DeWitt, New York|DeWitt]], [[Chenango, New York|Chenango]], [[Spafford, New York|Spafford]], [[LaFayette, New York|Lafayette]], [[Albany, New York|Albany]], [[Salina, New York|Salina]], [[Skaneateles (town), New York|Skaneateles]] and [[Geddes, New York|Geddes]],\n*Company I at [[Hart Island (Bronx)|Hart's Island]], [[Kingston, New York|Kingston]], [[Poughkeepsie, New York|Poughkeepsie]], [[Jamaica, Queens|Jamaica]], [[Tarrytown, New York|Tarrytown]] and Albany,\n*Company K at [[Mount Morris, New York|Mount Morris]], [[Goshen, New York|Goshen]], [[Farmington, New York|Farmington]], Poughkeepsie, [[Avon, New York|Avon]], [[Hopewell, New York|Hopewell]] and Elmira, and\n*Companies L and M at New York City and [[Brooklyn]].{{Sfn|Phisterer|1912|p=751}}\n\nHarhaus was mustered out on September 10, leaving regimental Major Walter Clark Hull in command. Hull was promoted to colonel on November 1, but was killed in a skirmish at Cedar Creek on November 12.{{Sfn|Adjutant General of New York|1868|p=11}} After the death of Hull, Lieutenant Colonel Mortimer B. Birdseye was temporarily in command of the regiment from December 1. Colonel [[Alanson M. Randol]] took command of the regiment on December 23, which he led for the rest of the war.{{Sfn|Phisterer|1912|p=754}} The 2nd New York remained with the Cavalry Corps until being transferred to serve with the cavalry of the [[Army of the Shenandoah (Union)|Army of the Shenandoah]] in October 1864, before returning to the Army of the Potomac in March 1865.{{Sfn|Phisterer|1912|p=751}} \n\nAt the [[Battle of Appomattox Station]] on April 8, the regiment, advancing at the head of [[Alexander Cummings McWhorter Pennington Jr.|Pennington]]'s Brigade, captured three Confederate railroad trains loaded with supplies at the station. To secure the trains from nearby Confederate cavalry, Randol ordered the trains crewed with soldiers who were former railwaymen, who drove the trains toward [[Edward Ord]]'s column.{{Sfn|Longacre|2003|p=|pp=171\u2013172}} Randol and the eight companies recruited in 1864 mustered out on June 5 at [[Alexandria,  Virginia]], followed by the remaining four companies on June 23.{{Sfn|Phisterer|1912|p=751}}\n\nDuring its service, seven officers and 67 enlisted men were killed in action, two officers and 47 enlisted men died of wounds, and three officers and 246 enlisted men died of disease and other causes for total deaths of twelve officers and 360 enlisted men. Of these, one officer and 106 enlisted men died while in [[American Civil War prison camps|Confederate prisons]].{{Sfn|Phisterer|1912|p=751}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of New York Civil War units]]\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n=== Bibliography ===\n*{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N-9GAQAAMAAJ|title=Annual Report of the Adjutant General of New York|last=Adjutant General of New York|first=|publisher=Printing House of Charles Van Benthuysen and Sons|year=1868|isbn=|volume=2|location=Albany|pages=|ref=harv}} \u2013 Contains ''Register of Officers Commissioned in Volunteer Regiments from the state of New York, 1861\u20131865.''\n*{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/08697590.3359.emory.edu|title=A Compendium of the War of the Rebellion|last=Dyer|first=Frederick H.|publisher=Dyer Publishing Company|year=1908|isbn=|location=Des Moines, IA|pages=|oclc=8697590|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Chancellorsville|last=Greene|first=A. Wilson|publisher=University of North Carolina Press|year=2009|isbn=9781469602400|editor-last=Gallagher|editor-first=Gary W.|location=Chapel Hill|pages=65\u2013106|chapter=Stoneman's Raid|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|title=A Campaign of Giants: The Battle for Petersburg|last=Greene|first=A. Wilson|publisher=University of North Carolina Press|year=2018|isbn=9781469638577|volume=1: From the Crossing of the James to the Crater|location=Chapel Hill|pages=|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Longacre|first=Edward G.|title=The Cavalry at Appomattox: A Tactical Study of Mounted Operations During the Civil War's Climactic Campaign, March 27 \u2013 April 9, 1865|location=Mechanicsburg, PA|publisher=Stackpole Books|year=2003|ISBN=978-0-8117-0051-1|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l7k6AQAAMAAJ|title=Final Report on the Battlefield of Gettysburg|last=New York Monuments Commission for the Battlefields of Gettysburg and Chattanooga|first=|publisher=J.B. Lyon Company|year=1900|isbn=|volume=3|location=Albany|pages=|chapter=}}\n**{{Cite book|url=|title=Final Report on the Battlefield of Gettysburg|last=Birdseye|first=Mortimer B.|publisher=J.B. Lyon Company|year=1900|isbn=|volume=3|location=Albany|pages=1099\u20131102|chapter=Historical Sketch|ref=harv}}\n**{{Cite book|url=|title=Final Report on the Battlefield of Gettysburg|last=Glazier|first=Willard|publisher=J.B. Lyon Company|year=1900|isbn=|volume=3|location=Albany|pages=1102\u20131109|chapter=The \"Harris Light.\": Historical Sketch|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|url=https://dmna.ny.gov/historic/research/DigBooks/Phisterer_NYWarOfTheRebellion/Phisterer_NewYorkInTheWarOfTheRebellion_V1.pdf|title=New York in the War of the Rebellion|last=Phisterer|first=Frederick|publisher=J. B. Lyon Company|year=1912|isbn=|edition=3rd|volume=1|location=Albany|pages=|ref=harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://dmna.ny.gov/historic/reghist/civil/cavalry/2ndCav/2ndCavMain.htm 2nd New York Cavalry Regiment page at New York State Division of Military and Naval Affairs Unit History Project]\n* [https://www.loc.gov/item/ihas.200001997/ Song of the Harris Light Cavalry, 1863 at Library of Congress]\n\n\n[[Category:New York (state) Civil War regiments]]\n[[Category:1861 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the regiment nicknamed the Harris Light|the unit nicknamed the Northern Black Horse also designated by New York state authority as the 2nd Cavalry|7th Regiment New York Volunteer Cavalry}}{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name = 2nd New York Volunteer Cavalry Regiment\n| image = \n| dates = October 8, 1861\u2013June 5, 1865\n| country = {{flag|United States of America|1863}}\n| allegiance = [[Union (Civil War)|Union]]\n| branch = [[Union Army]]\n| type = [[Cavalry in the American Civil War|Cavalry]]\n| nickname = Harris Light Cavalry\n| battles = [[American Civil War]]\n| notable_commanders = Col. [[Judson Kilpatrick]]<br />Col. [[Henry Eugene Davies]]<br />Col. [[Alanson M. Randol]]\n}}\n\n[[File:Private Thomas Dennis of Co. G, 2nd New York Cavalry Regiment in uniform with American flag LOC ppmsca.52246.jpg|thumb|right|Private Thomas Dennis of Co. G, 2nd New York Cavalry Regiment. From the Liljenquist Family Collection of Civil War Photographs, Prints and Photographs Division, [[Library of Congress]]]]\n\nThe '''2nd New York Volunteer Cavalry Regiment''' was a unit of the [[Union Army]] during the [[American Civil War]]. It served with the [[Army of the Potomac]] and fought in [[Stoneman's 1863 raid]], the [[Wilson\u2013Kautz Raid]], and the [[Battle of Appomattox Station]].\n\n==History==\nColonel J. Mansfield Davies was authorized by the [[War Department (US)|War Department]] to recruit the regiment, unofficially known as the Harris Light Cavalry, on July, 25, 1861. Its twelve companies were recruited as follows: \n\n* Company A at New York City, [[Hartford, Connecticut]], and [[Newton, New Jersey]], \n* Company B at Newton and [[Deckertown|Deckertown, New Jersey]], \n* Companies C and D \u2013 known as the Connecticut Squadron \u2013 at Hartford, \n*Company E at New York City, [[Troy, New York|Troy]], [[Fort Edward (town), New York|Fort Edward]], and [[Cambridge, New York]],\n* Company F at [[Covington, Indiana]], [[Fairfield, Vermont]], Troy, and [[Richfield Springs, New York]], \n* Company G at New York City, [[Newburgh, New York|Newburgh]], and Fort Edward, \n* Company H at [[Chambersburg, Indiana]], I at [[Lafayette, Indiana]], \n* Company K at [[Scranton, Pennsylvania]], [[Hampton, New Jersey|Hampton]], [[Newark, New Jersey|Newark]], and [[Rockaway, New Jersey]], New York City, Troy, and Richfield Springs, \n* Company L at New York City, [[Hudson, New York|Hudson]], Troy, [[Fort Ann, New York|Fort Ann]], Fort Edward and [[Litchfield, New York|Litchfield]], and\n* Company M at New York City, Newburgh, [[Plattsburgh (city), New York|Plattsburgh]] and [[Port Henry, New York|Port Henry]].{{Sfn|Phisterer|1912|p=751}}\n\nThe regiment was organized at [[Scarsdale, New York]], where it was mustered into Federal service for a term of three years between August 9 and October 8, 1861. The War Department designated the regiment as the 7th United States Cavalry on October 26, but it was transferred to New York state service as the 2nd New York Volunteer Cavalry,{{Sfn|Phisterer|1912|p=751}} as Congress had not provided for a seventh [[Regular Army (United States)|Regular Army]] cavalry regiment.{{Sfn|Dyer|1908|p=1370}}\n\nAfter leaving New York during September and October, the regiment served with [[Irvin McDowell|McDowell]]'s Division of the [[Army of the Potomac]] from the latter month,  on duty in the defenses of [[Washington, D.C.|Washington, D.C]].{{Sfn|Dyer|1908|p=1370}} It was transferred to the Third Division of the [[I Corps (Union Army)|First Corps]] of the Army of the Potomac in March 1862, and in May briefly became part of [[Rufus King (general)|King]]'s Division of the [[Department of the Rappahannock]]. The 2nd New York Volunteer Cavalry formed part of the Cavalry Brigade of the Second Division of the Third Corps of the [[Army of Virginia]] (temporarily redesignated from the First Corps) from June. It was transferred to [[George D. Bayard|Bayard]]'s Cavalry Brigade of the Army of the Potomac in September, while Companies A, B, I, and K were detached to the Third Division of the First Corps during September and October. J. Mansfield Davies resigned on December 6, and was replaced as colonel by regimental Lieutenant Colonel [[Judson Kilpatrick]].{{Sfn|Phisterer|1912|p=754}}<ref>https://catalog.archives.gov/id/76062574</ref> After Bayard's death, the brigade that included the regiment came under the command of Brigadier General [[David McMurtrie Gregg]] on December 15.{{Sfn|Phisterer|1912|p=751}}\n[[File:2nd-NY-Cav-Monument.jpg|thumb|Monument to the 2nd New York Cavalry at Gettysburg]]\nThe 2nd New York was assigned to the First Brigade of the Third Division of the [[Cavalry Corps (Union Army)|Cavalry Corps]] of the Army of the Potomac on February 11, 1863, detaching a battalion to the First Brigade of the First Division of the [[IV Corps (Union Army)|Fourth Corps]] for service on the [[Virginia Peninsula]] between May and July. During [[Stoneman's 1863 raid]], the regiment was sent against Richmond and the [[Chickahominy River|Chickahominy]] railroad bridges.{{Sfn|Greene|2009|p=83}} After Kilpatrick was promoted to brigadier general on June 13, Lieutenant Colonel [[Henry Eugene Davies|Henry E. Davies]] was promoted to colonel in his stead three days later.{{Sfn|Phisterer|1912|p=754}} The regiment was transferred to the Second Brigade of the Second Division of the cavalry of the Army of the Potomac on June 14.{{Sfn|Phisterer|1912|p=751}} \n\nIt again returned to the First Brigade of the Third Division of the Cavalry Corps on August 12. Davies was promoted to brigadier general on September 16, leaving regimental Lieutenant Colonel Otto Harhaus, promoted to colonel on April 1, 1864, in command.{{Sfn|Phisterer|1912|p=754}} During the [[Wilson\u2013Kautz Raid]], on June 23, 1864, the regiment tore up tracks on the [[Southside Railroad (Virginia)|South Side Railroad]] at Ford's Depot.{{Sfn|Greene|2018|p=574n53}} When the regimental term of service expired, those who had served out their terms were discharged and on August 29, the recruits and reenlisted veterans of the 2nd New York Volunteer Cavalry was consolidated into a four-company battalion including Companies A, B, C, and D that continued in service. Eight new companies, recruited for a one year term of service, expanded the 2nd New York Cavalry to a regiment again by their addition in September and October.{{Sfn|Phisterer|1912|p=751}} \n\nThe eight new companies were recruited as follows:\n\n*Company E \u2013 known as the Ticonderoga Cavalry Company \u2013 at Plattsburgh and [[Ticonderoga, New York|Ticonderoga]],\n*Company F at [[Elmira, New York|Elmira]] and [[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]],\n*Companies G and H at [[Manlius, New York|Manlius]], [[Rochester, New York|Rochester]], [[Elbridge, New York|Elbridge]], [[Onondaga, New York|Onondaga]], Syracuse, [[Cicero, New York|Cicero]], [[Pompey, New York|Pompey]], [[DeWitt, New York|DeWitt]], [[Chenango, New York|Chenango]], [[Spafford, New York|Spafford]], [[LaFayette, New York|Lafayette]], [[Albany, New York|Albany]], [[Salina, New York|Salina]], [[Skaneateles (town), New York|Skaneateles]] and [[Geddes, New York|Geddes]],\n*Company I at [[Hart Island (Bronx)|Hart's Island]], [[Kingston, New York|Kingston]], [[Poughkeepsie, New York|Poughkeepsie]], [[Jamaica, Queens|Jamaica]], [[Tarrytown, New York|Tarrytown]] and Albany,\n*Company K at [[Mount Morris, New York|Mount Morris]], [[Goshen, New York|Goshen]], [[Farmington, New York|Farmington]], Poughkeepsie, [[Avon, New York|Avon]], [[Hopewell, New York|Hopewell]] and Elmira, and\n*Companies L and M at New York City and [[Brooklyn]].{{Sfn|Phisterer|1912|p=751}}\n\nHarhaus was mustered out on September 10, leaving regimental Major Walter Clark Hull in command. Hull was promoted to colonel on November 1, but was killed in a skirmish at Cedar Creek on November 12.{{Sfn|Adjutant General of New York|1868|p=11}} After the death of Hull, Lieutenant Colonel Mortimer B. Birdseye was temporarily in command of the regiment from December 1. Colonel [[Alanson M. Randol]] took command of the regiment on December 23, which he led for the rest of the war.{{Sfn|Phisterer|1912|p=754}} The 2nd New York remained with the Cavalry Corps until being transferred to serve with the cavalry of the [[Army of the Shenandoah (Union)|Army of the Shenandoah]] in October 1864, before returning to the Army of the Potomac in March 1865.{{Sfn|Phisterer|1912|p=751}} \n\nAt the [[Battle of Appomattox Station]] on April 8, the regiment, advancing at the head of [[Alexander Cummings McWhorter Pennington Jr.|Pennington]]'s Brigade, captured three Confederate railroad trains loaded with supplies at the station. To secure the trains from nearby Confederate cavalry, Randol ordered the trains crewed with soldiers who were former railwaymen, who drove the trains toward [[Edward Ord]]'s column.{{Sfn|Longacre|2003|p=|pp=171\u2013172}} Randol and the eight companies recruited in 1864 mustered out on June 5 at [[Alexandria,  Virginia]], followed by the remaining four companies on June 23.{{Sfn|Phisterer|1912|p=751}}\n\nDuring its service, seven officers and 67 enlisted men were killed in action, two officers and 47 enlisted men died of wounds, and three officers and 246 enlisted men died of disease and other causes for total deaths of twelve officers and 360 enlisted men. Of these, one officer and 106 enlisted men died while in [[American Civil War prison camps|Confederate prisons]].{{Sfn|Phisterer|1912|p=751}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of New York Civil War units]]\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n=== Bibliography ===\n*{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N-9GAQAAMAAJ|title=Annual Report of the Adjutant General of New York|last=Adjutant General of New York|first=|publisher=Printing House of Charles Van Benthuysen and Sons|year=1868|isbn=|volume=2|location=Albany|pages=|ref=harv}} \u2013 Contains ''Register of Officers Commissioned in Volunteer Regiments from the state of New York, 1861\u20131865.''\n*{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/08697590.3359.emory.edu|title=A Compendium of the War of the Rebellion|last=Dyer|first=Frederick H.|publisher=Dyer Publishing Company|year=1908|isbn=|location=Des Moines, IA|pages=|oclc=8697590|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Chancellorsville|last=Greene|first=A. Wilson|publisher=University of North Carolina Press|year=2009|isbn=9781469602400|editor-last=Gallagher|editor-first=Gary W.|location=Chapel Hill|pages=65\u2013106|chapter=Stoneman's Raid|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|title=A Campaign of Giants: The Battle for Petersburg|last=Greene|first=A. Wilson|publisher=University of North Carolina Press|year=2018|isbn=9781469638577|volume=1: From the Crossing of the James to the Crater|location=Chapel Hill|pages=|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Longacre|first=Edward G.|title=The Cavalry at Appomattox: A Tactical Study of Mounted Operations During the Civil War's Climactic Campaign, March 27 \u2013 April 9, 1865|location=Mechanicsburg, PA|publisher=Stackpole Books|year=2003|ISBN=978-0-8117-0051-1|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l7k6AQAAMAAJ|title=Final Report on the Battlefield of Gettysburg|last=New York Monuments Commission for the Battlefields of Gettysburg and Chattanooga|first=|publisher=J.B. Lyon Company|year=1900|isbn=|volume=3|location=Albany|pages=|chapter=}}\n**{{Cite book|url=|title=Final Report on the Battlefield of Gettysburg|last=Birdseye|first=Mortimer B.|publisher=J.B. Lyon Company|year=1900|isbn=|volume=3|location=Albany|pages=1099\u20131102|chapter=Historical Sketch|ref=harv}}\n**{{Cite book|url=|title=Final Report on the Battlefield of Gettysburg|last=Glazier|first=Willard|publisher=J.B. Lyon Company|year=1900|isbn=|volume=3|location=Albany|pages=1102\u20131109|chapter=The \"Harris Light.\": Historical Sketch|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|url=https://dmna.ny.gov/historic/research/DigBooks/Phisterer_NYWarOfTheRebellion/Phisterer_NewYorkInTheWarOfTheRebellion_V1.pdf|title=New York in the War of the Rebellion|last=Phisterer|first=Frederick|publisher=J. B. Lyon Company|year=1912|isbn=|edition=3rd|volume=1|location=Albany|pages=|ref=harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://dmna.ny.gov/historic/reghist/civil/cavalry/2ndCav/2ndCavMain.htm 2nd New York Cavalry Regiment page at New York State Division of Military and Naval Affairs Unit History Project]\n* [https://www.loc.gov/item/ihas.200001997/ Song of the Harris Light Cavalry, 1863 at Library of Congress]\n\n\n[[Category:New York (state) Civil War regiments]]\n[[Category:1861 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "Hhfjbaker", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2nd_New_York_Volunteer_Cavalry_Regiment"}
{"title_page": "Ern\u0151 Rubik", "text_new": "{{for|his father|Ern\u0151 Rubik (aircraft designer)}}\n{{eastern name order|Rubik Ern\u0151}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Ern\u0151 Rubik\n\n| image =Erno_Rubik_Genius_Gala_2014.jpg\n| image_size =\n| caption = Rubik at the 2014 Genius Gala\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1944|07|13}}\n| birth_place = [[Budapest]], Hungary\n| death_date =\n| death_place = \n| death_cause =\n| resting_place =\n| resting_place_coordinates =\n| residence =\n| nationality = Hungarian\n| other_names =\n| known_for = Puzzle designer of Rubik's Cube, inventor, architect, professor\n| education = 1962\u201367 University of Technology, Budapest (architecture)<br>1967\u201371 Hungarian Academy of Applied Arts; Interior Architecture and Design\n| employer = Rubik Brand Ltd. (UK)\n| occupation = Inventor, designer, board executive\n| title = Chairman\n| salary =\n| networth =\n| height =\n| weight =\n| term =\n| predecessor =\n| successor =\n| party =\n| boards = Judit Polgar Foundation\n| signature =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''Ern\u0151 Rubik''' ({{IPA-hu|\u02c8rubik \u02c8\u025brn\u00f8\u02d0|lang}}; born 13 July 1944) is a Hungarian inventor, architect and professor of architecture. He is best known for the invention of [[mechanical puzzle]]s including [[Rubik's Cube]] (1974), [[Rubik's Magic]], [[Rubik's Magic#Rubik.27s Magic: Master Edition|Rubik's Magic: Master Edition]], and [[Rubik's Snake]].<ref name=\"sporting\">{{Cite book |author=William Fotheringham |title=Fotheringham's Sporting Pastimes |publisher=Anova Books |year=2007 |page=[https://archive.org/details/fotheringhamsext0000foth/page/50 50] |isbn=1-86105-953-1 |url=https://archive.org/details/fotheringhamsext0000foth/page/50 }}</ref>\n\nWhile Rubik became famous for inventing the Rubik's Cube and his other puzzles, much of his recent work involves the promotion of science in education. Rubik is involved with several organisations such as Beyond Rubik's Cube, the Rubik Learning Initiative and the Judit Polgar Foundation all of whose aim is to engage students in science, mathematics, and problem solving at a young age.\n\n==Early life==\n\n===Childhood and parental influence===\nErn\u0151 Rubik was born in [[Budapest]], Hungary, 13 July 1944, during [[World War II]], and has lived all his life in Hungary. His father, [[Ern\u0151 Rubik (aircraft designer)|Ern\u0151 Rubik Sr.]], was a flight engineer at the [[Esztergom]] aircraft factory, and his mother, Magdolna Sz\u00e1nt\u00f3, was a poet.<ref name=\"ref1\">{{cite book|last=|first=|authorlink=|author2=|title=International Who's Who 2000|publisher=Europa|year=1999|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/internationalwho0000unse/page/1342 1342]|url=https://archive.org/details/internationalwho0000unse/page/1342|isbn=1-85743-050-6|url-access=registration}}</ref> He has stated in almost every interview that he got his inspiration from his father.\n\nHis father, Ern\u0151 Sr., was a highly respected engineer of [[Glider (aircraft)|gliders]]. His extensive work and expertise in this area gained him an international reputation as an expert in his field. Ern\u0151 Rubik has stated that:<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n\n{{quote|Beside him I learned a lot about work in the sense of a value-creating process which has a target, and a positive result too. Both figuratively and literally he was a person capable of 'moving a hill'. There was nothing that could prevent him from doing what he decided or bringing a project to a completion, if necessary even with his own hands. No work was unworthy or undeserving for him.}}\n\nRubik studied sculpture at the Technical University in Budapest and architecture at the Academy of Applied Arts and Design, also in Budapest. While a professor of design at the academy, he pursued his hobby of building geometric models. One of these was a prototype of his cube, made of 27 wooden blocks; it took Rubik a month to solve the problem of the cube. It proved a useful tool for teaching algebraic group theory, and in late 1977 Konsumex, Hungary's state trading company, began marketing it. By 1980 Rubik's Cube was marketed throughout the world, and over 100 million authorized units, with an estimated 50 million unauthorized imitations, were sold, mostly during its subsequent three years of popularity. Approximately 50 books were published describing how to solve the puzzle of Rubik's Cube. Following his cube's popularity, Rubik opened a studio to develop designs in 1984; among its products was another popular puzzle toy, Rubik's Magic.\n\n===Education===\nFrom 1958 to 1962, Rubik specialised in sculpture at the Secondary School of Fine and Applied Arts. From 1962 to 1967, Rubik attended the [[Budapest University of Technology and Economics|Budapest University of Technology]] where he became a member of the Architecture Faculty. From 1967 to 1971, Rubik attended the Hungarian Academy of Applied Arts and was on the Faculty of Interior Architecture and Design.<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n\nRubik considers university and the education it afforded him as the decisive event which shaped his life. Rubik has stated that \"Schools offered me the opportunity to acquire knowledge of subjects or rather crafts that need a lot of practice, persistence and diligence with the direction of a mentor.\"<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early professorship and birth of Rubik's Cube===\nFrom 1971 to 1979, Rubik was a professor of architecture at the [[Hungarian University of Applied Arts|Budapest College of Applied Arts]] (''Iparm\u0171v\u00e9szeti F\u0151iskola''). It was during his time there that he built designs for a three-dimensional puzzle and completed the first working prototype of the [[Rubik's Cube]] in 1974, applying for a patent on the puzzle in 1975. In an interview with [[CNN]], Rubik stated that he was \"searching to find a good task for my students.\"<ref name=\"CNN\">[http://www.cnn.com/2012/10/10/tech/rubiks-cube-inventor The little cube that changed the world] Retrieved 2013-04-29.</ref>\n\n{{quote|Space always intrigued me, with its incredibly rich possibilities, space alteration by (architectural) objects, objects' transformation in space (sculpture, design), movement in space and in time, their correlation, their repercussion on mankind, the relation between man and space, the object and time. I think the CUBE arose from this interest, from this search for expression and for this always more increased acuteness of these thoughts...}}\n\n[[File:Rubik's cube v3.svg|thumb|Rubik's Cube]]\n\n===From classroom tool to Magic Cube to Rubik's Cube===\nStarting with blocks of wood and rubber bands, Rubik set out to create a structure which would allow the individual pieces to move without the whole structure falling apart. Rubik originally used wood for the block because of the convenience of a workshop at the university and because he viewed wood as a simple material to work with that did not require sophisticated machinery. Rubik made the original prototypes of his cube by hand, cutting the wood, boring the holes and using elastic bands to hold the contraption together.<ref name=\"CNN\"/>\n\nRubik showed his prototype to his class and his students liked it very much. Rubik realized that, because of the cube's simple structure, it could be manufactured relatively easily and might have appeal to a larger audience. Rubik's father possessed several patents, so Rubik was familiar with the process and applied for a patent for his invention. Rubik then set out to find a manufacturer in Hungary, but had great difficulty due to the rigid planned economy of Hungary at the time. Eventually, Rubik was able to find a small company that worked with plastic and made chess pieces.<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/> The cube was originally known in Hungary as the 'Magic Cube'.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rubik's Cube|url=https://www.firstversions.com/2015/08/rubiks-cube.html|publisher=First Versions|date=|access-date=4 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nRubik licensed the Magic Cube to [[Ideal Toys]], a US company in 1979. Ideal rebranded The Magic Cube to the Rubik's Cube before its introduction to an international audience in 1980.<ref name=\"IBT\">Villapaz, Luke.[http://www.ibtimes.com/rubiks-cube-40th-anniversary-9-facts-behind-famous-3-d-toy-puzzle-1576562 \"Rubik's Cube 40th Anniversary: 9 Facts Behind The Famous 3-D Toy Puzzle\"].International Business Times, 25 April 2014. Retrieved 6 May 2014</ref><ref>[https://uk.rubiks.com/about/the-history-of-the-rubiks-cube \"The history of Rubik's Cube\"], Rubik's:The home of Rubik's Cube, retrieved and [https://web.archive.org/web/20170207112606/https://www.rubiks.com/about/the-history-of-the-rubiks-cube archived] 6 February 2017</ref> The process from early prototype to significant mass production of the Cube had taken over six years.<ref name=\"CNN\"/> The Rubik's Cube would go on to become an instant success worldwide, winning several Toy of the Year awards, and becoming a staple of 1980's popular culture. To date, over 350 million Rubik's Cubes have been sold, making it one of the best selling toys of all time.<ref name=\"IBT\"/><ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/science/rubiks-cube-25-years-on-crazy-toys-crazy-times-5334529.html \"Rubik's Cube 25 years on: crazy toys, crazy times\"], ''Independent'', 15 August 2007.</ref>\n\n===Other inventions===\nIn addition to Rubik's Cube, Rubik is also the inventor of [[Rubik's Magic]], [[Rubik's Snake]] and [[Rubik's 360]] among others.<ref>{{cite web|title=Japan teen in historic Rubik win|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/7033519.stm|publisher=BBC News|date=8 October 2007|access-date=4 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Later career and other works===\nIn the early 1980s, he became the editor of a game and puzzle journal called ''..\u00c9s j\u00e1t\u00e9k'' (''...And games''), then became self-employed in 1983, founding the Rubik St\u00fadi\u00f3, where he designed furniture and games. In 1987 he became a professor with full tenure; in 1990 he became the president of the Hungarian Engineering Academy (''Magyar M\u00e9rn\u00f6ki Akad\u00e9mia''). At the Academy, he created the International Rubik Foundation to support especially talented young engineers and industrial designers.\n\nIn 2009, he was appointed as an honorary professor of [[Keimyung University]], Daegu, South Korea.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2017/07/178_52464.html|newspaper=The Korea Times|title=Cube Exhibition May Come to Korea|date=2009-09-24}}</ref>\n\n==Work and engagements in the 2010s==\nIn the 2010s, Rubik has recently spent much of his time working on ''Beyond Rubik's Cube'', a Science, Technology, Engineering, Mathematics ([[STEM fields]]) based exhibition, which will travel the globe over the next six years{{when|date=January 2020}}.<ref>[http://brc.lsc.org/ \"Beyond Rubik's Cube\"] Liberty Science Center, N.D. Retrieved 6 May 2014</ref> The grand opening of the exhibit was held on 26 April 2014 at the [[Liberty Science Center]] in New Jersey. At the exhibition, Rubik gave several lectures, tours, and engaged with the public and several members of the [[speedcubing]] crowd in attendance, including [[Anthony Michael Brooks]], a world-class speedcuber.<ref>Barron, James. [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/26/nyregion/rubiks-redux-a-colorful-cube-puzzles-anew.html?hpw&rref=nyregion \"A Cube With a Twist: At 40, It Puzzles Anew\"]. The New York Times, 25 April 2014. retrieved 6 May 2014</ref><ref>Matheson Whitney. [https://www.usatoday.com/story/popcandy/2014/04/25/rubiks-cube/8141175/ \"Forty years later, the Rubik's Cube still puzzles\"]. USA Today, 25 April 2014. Retrieved 6 May 2014</ref>\n\n==Influences==\nErn\u0151 Rubik has listed several individuals who, as he has said, \"exerted a great influence over me through their work.\" These include [[Leonardo da Vinci]], whom Rubik regards as ''the'' [[Renaissance man]]; [[Michelangelo]], whom he respects as a [[polymath]], painter, and sculptor; and artist [[M.C. Escher]], who drew impossible constructions and grappled with explorations of [[infinity]]. As regards to philosophers and writers, Rubik admires [[Voltaire]], [[Stendhal]], [[Thomas Mann]], [[Jean-Paul Sartre]], Hungarian poet [[Attila J\u00f3zsef]], [[Jules Verne]], and [[Isaac Asimov]]. In the field of architecture, Rubik is an admirer of [[Frank Lloyd Wright]] and [[Le Corbusier]].<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n\n==Cultural and leisure pursuits==\nRubik admits to being a lifelong bibliophile and has stated, \"Books offered me the possibility of gaining knowledge of the World, Nature and People.\" Rubik has stated that he has a special interest in science fiction.\n\nRubik is fond of outdoor activities such as walking through nature, playing sports, and sailing on [[Lake Balaton]]. Rubik is also an avid gardener and has stated that \"collecting succulents is my favourite pastime.\"<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n\n==Prizes and awards==\n* 1978 \u2013 Budapest International Trade Fair, Prize for the Cube<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\">[http://www.create2009.europa.eu/ambassadors/profiles/erno_rubik.html Europa Interview with Ern\u0151 Rubik] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328175740/http://www.create2009.europa.eu/ambassadors/profiles/erno_rubik.html |date=28 March 2016 }} Retrieved 5 May 2014</ref>\n* 1980 \u2013 Toy of the Year: Federal Republic of Germany, United Kingdom, France, USA<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n* 1981 \u2013 Toy of the Year: Finland, Sweden, Italy<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n* 1982 \u2013 Toy of the Year: United Kingdom (second time)<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n* 1982 \u2013 The Museum of Modern Art, New York selected Rubik's Cube into its permanent collection<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n* 1983 \u2013 Hungarian State Prize for demonstrating and teaching 3D structures and for the various solutions that inspired scientific researches in several ways<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n* 1988 \u2013 Juvenile Prize from the State Office of Youth and Sport<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n* 1995 \u2013 D\u00e9nes Gabor Prize from the Novofer Foundation as an acknowledgement of achievements in the field of innovation<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n* Life is a wonder! JK YOU DUMB -Luca the BlackMachine\n* 1996 \u2013 \u00c1nyos Jedlik Prize from the Hungarian Patent Office<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n* 1997 \u2013 Prize for the Reputation of Hungary (1997)<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n* 2007 \u2013 [[Kossuth Prize]] the most prestigious cultural award in Hungary<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n* 2008 \u2013 Moholy-Nagy Prize \u2013 from the Moholy-Nagy University of Arts and Design<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n* 2009 \u2013 EU Ambassador of the Year of Creativity and Innovation<ref>[http://www.create2009.europa.eu/press/news_archive/news_singleview/news/rubiks-cube-and-eu-politics-the-manifesto-for-creativity-and-innovation-in-europe.html Rubik's cube and EU Politics: The Manifesto for Creativity and Innovation in Europe Retrieved] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923211031/http://www.create2009.europa.eu/press/news_archive/news_singleview/news/rubiks-cube-and-eu-politics-the-manifesto-for-creativity-and-innovation-in-europe.html |date=23 September 2015 }} 5 May 2014</ref>\n* 2010 \u2013 USA Science and Engineering Festival Award (Outstanding Contribution to Science Education)<ref>[http://www.ait-budapest.com/news/ait-faculty-member-erno-rubik-is-honored-with-the-outstanding-contributions-to-science-educatio Ern\u0151 Rubik Awarded with the Outstanding Contributions to Science Education Award] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505072116/http://www.ait-budapest.com/news/ait-faculty-member-erno-rubik-is-honored-with-the-outstanding-contributions-to-science-educatio |date=5 May 2014 }} Retrieved 5 May 2014</ref>\n* 2010 \u2013 The Hungarian Order of Merit Commanders Cross with the Star\n* 2010 \u2013 Prima Primissima Prize\n* 2012 \u2013 My Country Awards\n* 2014 \u2013 Grand Cross of the Order of Saint Stephen (The highest medal awarded by Hungary)<ref>[http://www.daijiworld.com/news/news_disp.asp?n_id=257363 Ern\u0151 Rubik Awarded the Highest Medal Awarded by the country of Hungary] Retrieved 23 August 2014</ref>\n* 2014 \u2013 Honorary Citizen of Budapest<ref>[http://annyiversary.blogspot.hu/2014_07_01_archive.html Ern\u0151 Rubik Named as an Honorary Citizen of Budapest] Retrieved 23 August 2014</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nEditor and co-author of ''A b\u0171v\u00f6s kocka'' (\"The Magic Cube\"), M\u0171szaki Kiad\u00f3, Budapest, 1981.\n\nCo-author of ''The Rubik's Cube Compendium'' (written by David Singmaster, Ern\u0151 Rubik, Gerzson K\u00e9ri, Gy\u00f6rgy Marx, Tam\u00e1s Varga and Tam\u00e1s Vekerdy), Oxford University Press, 1987.<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/Rubiks-Cubic-Compendium-Recreations-Mathematics/dp/0198532024/ref=sr_1_2?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1399393012&sr=1-2 The Rubik\u2019s Cube Compendium]</ref>\n\n==Foundations and appearances==\nHe attended the 2007 World Championship in Budapest.<ref>John Nadler, [http://www.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,1669535,00.html \"Squaring Up to the Rubik's Cube\"], ''Time'', 9 October 2007.</ref><ref>[http://www.rubiks.com/~/media/Files/media_vault/Media%20folder_press_releases/July%202007%20%20%20%20Erno%20Rubik%20interview.ashx \"25 years on\"] Erno Rubik interview at the Rubik's Cube official website, retrieved 9 May 2010</ref> He also gave a lecture and autograph session at the \"Bridges-Pecs\" conference (\"Bridges between Mathematics and the Arts\") in July 2010.<ref>[http://bridgesmathart.org/bridges-2010/2010-plenary-speakers/ \"Bridges Conference\"] List of Plenary speakers, retrieved 26 July 2010</ref>\n\nRubik is a member of the [[USA Science and Engineering Festival]]'s Advisory Board.<ref>[http://www.usasciencefestival.org/about/advisors US Science and Engineering Festival Advisors] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100421005310/http://www.usasciencefestival.org/about/advisors/ |date=21 April 2010 }} Retrieved 2010-07-05.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://cubeland.free.fr/infos/ernorubik.htm An interview with Ern\u0151 Rubik]\n* [https://orszaginfo.magyarorszag.hu/informaciok/hiresmagyarok/rubikerno.html His biography at Hungary.hu] {{in lang|hu}}\n* [http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1874509,00.html His first print interview in ten years]\n* [http://www.time.com/rubik An exclusive video interview about the new Rubik's 360]\n\n{{Rubik's Cube}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rubik, Erno}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Budapest]]\n[[Category:Hungarian architects]]\n[[Category:Hungarian inventors]]\n[[Category:Recreational mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Puzzle designers]]\n[[Category:Rubik's Cube]]\n[[Category:Toy inventors]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|his father|Ern\u0151 Rubik (aircraft designer)}}\n{{eastern name order|Rubik Ern\u0151}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Ern\u0151 Rubik\n\n| image =Erno_Rubik_Genius_Gala_2014.jpg\n| image_size =\n| caption = Rubik at the 2014 Genius Gala\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1944|07|13}}\n| birth_place = [[Budapest]], Hungary\n| death_date =\n| death_place = \n| death_cause =\n| resting_place =\n| resting_place_coordinates =\n| residence =\n| nationality = Hungarian\n| other_names =\n| known_for = Puzzle designer of Rubik's Cube, inventor, architect, professor\n| education = 1962\u201367 University of Technology, Budapest (architecture)<br>1967\u201371 Hungarian Academy of Applied Arts; Interior Architecture and Design\n| employer = Rubik Brand Ltd. (UK)\n| occupation = Inventor, designer, board executive\n| title = Chairman\n| salary =\n| networth =\n| height =\n| weight =\n| term =\n| predecessor =\n| successor =\n| party =\n| boards = Judit Polgar Foundation\n| signature =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''Ern\u0151 Rubik''' ({{IPA-hu|\u02c8rubik \u02c8\u025brn\u00f8\u02d0|lang}}; born 13 July 1944) is a Hungarian inventor, architect and professor of architecture. He is best known for the invention of [[mechanical puzzle]]s including [[Rubik's Cube]] (1974), [[Rubik's Magic]], [[Rubik's Magic#Rubik.27s Magic: Master Edition|Rubik's Magic: Master Edition]], and [[Rubik's Snake]].<ref name=\"sporting\">{{Cite book |author=William Fotheringham |title=Fotheringham's Sporting Pastimes |publisher=Anova Books |year=2007 |page=[https://archive.org/details/fotheringhamsext0000foth/page/50 50] |isbn=1-86105-953-1 |url=https://archive.org/details/fotheringhamsext0000foth/page/50 }}</ref>\n\nWhile Rubik became famous for inventing the Rubik's Cube and his other puzzles, much of his recent work involves the promotion of science in education. Rubik is involved with several organisations such as Beyond Rubik's Cube, the Rubik Learning Initiative and the Judit Polgar Foundation all of whose aim is to engage students in science, mathematics, and problem solving at a young age.\n\n==Early life==\n\n===Childhood and parental influence===\nErn\u0151 Rubik was born in [[Budapest]], Hungary, 13 July 1944, during [[World War II]], and has lived all his life in Hungary. His father, [[Ern\u0151 Rubik (aircraft designer)|Ern\u0151 Rubik Sr.]], was a flight engineer at the [[Esztergom]] aircraft factory, and his mother, Magdolna Sz\u00e1nt\u00f3, was a poet.<ref name=\"ref1\">{{cite book|last=|first=|authorlink=|author2=|title=International Who's Who 2000|publisher=Europa|year=1999|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/internationalwho0000unse/page/1342 1342]|url=https://archive.org/details/internationalwho0000unse/page/1342|isbn=1-85743-050-6|url-access=registration}}</ref> He has stated in almost every interview that he got his inspiration from his father.\n\nHis father, Ern\u0151 Sr., was a highly respected engineer of [[Glider (aircraft)|gliders]]. His extensive work and expertise in this area gained him an international reputation as an expert in his field. Ern\u0151 Rubik has stated that:<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n\n{{quote|Beside him I learned a lot about work in the sense of a value-creating process which has a target, and a positive result too. Both figuratively and literally he was a person capable of 'moving a hill'. There was nothing that could prevent him from doing what he decided or bringing a project to a completion, if necessary even with his own hands. No work was unworthy or undeserving for him.}}\n\nRubik studied sculpture at the Technical University in Budapest and architecture at the Academy of Applied Arts and Design, also in Budapest. While a professor of design at the academy, he pursued his hobby of building geometric models. One of these was a prototype of his cube, made of 27 wooden blocks; it took Rubik a month to solve the problem of the cube. It proved a useful tool for teaching algebraic group theory, and in late 1977 Konsumex, Hungary's state trading company, began marketing it. By 1980 Rubik's Cube was marketed throughout the world, and over 100 million authorized units, with an estimated 50 million unauthorized imitations, were sold, mostly during its subsequent three years of popularity. Approximately 50 books were published describing how to solve the puzzle of Rubik's Cube. Following his cube's popularity, Rubik opened a studio to develop designs in 1984; among its products was another popular puzzle toy, Rubik's Magic.\n\n===Education===\nFrom 1958 to 1962, Rubik specialised in sculpture at the Secondary School of Fine and Applied Arts. From 1962 to 1967, Rubik attended the [[Budapest University of Technology and Economics|Budapest University of Technology]] where he became a member of the Architecture Faculty. From 1967 to 1971, Rubik attended the Hungarian Academy of Applied Arts and was on the Faculty of Interior Architecture and Design.<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n\nRubik considers university and the education it afforded him as the decisive event which shaped his life. Rubik has stated that \"Schools offered me the opportunity to acquire knowledge of subjects or rather crafts that need a lot of practice, persistence and diligence with the direction of a mentor.\"<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early professorship and birth of Rubik's Cube===\nFrom 1971 to 1979, Rubik was a professor of architecture at the [[Hungarian University of Applied Arts|Budapest College of Applied Arts]] (''Iparm\u0171v\u00e9szeti F\u0151iskola''). It was during his time there that he built designs for a three-dimensional puzzle and completed the first working prototype of the [[Rubik's Cube]] in 1974, applying for a patent on the puzzle in 1975. In an interview with [[CNN]], Rubik stated that he was \"searching to find a good task for my students.\"<ref name=\"CNN\">[http://www.cnn.com/2012/10/10/tech/rubiks-cube-inventor The little cube that changed the world] Retrieved 2013-04-29.</ref>\n\n{{quote|Space always intrigued me, with its incredibly rich possibilities, space alteration by (architectural) objects, objects' transformation in space (sculpture, design), movement in space and in time, their correlation, their repercussion on mankind, the relation between man and space, the object and time. I think the CUBE arose from this interest, from this search for expression and for this always more increased acuteness of these thoughts...}}\n\n[[File:Rubik's cube v3.svg|thumb|Rubik's Cube]]\n\n===From classroom tool to Magic Cube to Rubik's Cube===\nStarting with blocks of wood and rubber bands, Rubik set out to create a structure which would allow the individual pieces to move without the whole structure falling apart. Rubik originally used wood for the block because of the convenience of a workshop at the university and because he viewed wood as a simple material to work with that did not require sophisticated machinery. Rubik made the original prototypes of his cube by hand, cutting the wood, boring the holes and using elastic bands to hold the contraption together.<ref name=\"CNN\"/>\n\nRubik showed his prototype to his class and his students liked it very much. Rubik realized that, because of the cube's simple structure, it could be manufactured relatively easily and might have appeal to a larger audience. Rubik's father possessed several patents, so Rubik was familiar with the process and applied for a patent for his invention. Rubik then set out to find a manufacturer in Hungary, but had great difficulty due to the rigid planned economy of Hungary at the time. Eventually, Rubik was able to find a small company that worked with plastic and made chess pieces.<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/> The cube was originally known in Hungary as the 'Magic Cube'.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rubik's Cube|url=https://www.firstversions.com/2015/08/rubiks-cube.html|publisher=First Versions|date=|access-date=4 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nRubik licensed the Magic Cube to [[Ideal Toys]], a US company in 1979. Ideal rebranded The Magic Cube to the Rubik's Cube before its introduction to an international audience in 1980.<ref name=\"IBT\">Villapaz, Luke.[http://www.ibtimes.com/rubiks-cube-40th-anniversary-9-facts-behind-famous-3-d-toy-puzzle-1576562 \"Rubik's Cube 40th Anniversary: 9 Facts Behind The Famous 3-D Toy Puzzle\"].International Business Times, 25 April 2014. Retrieved 6 May 2014</ref><ref>[https://uk.rubiks.com/about/the-history-of-the-rubiks-cube \"The history of Rubik's Cube\"], Rubik's:The home of Rubik's Cube, retrieved and [https://web.archive.org/web/20170207112606/https://www.rubiks.com/about/the-history-of-the-rubiks-cube archived] 6 February 2017</ref> The process from early prototype to significant mass production of the Cube had taken over six years.<ref name=\"CNN\"/> The Rubik's Cube would go on to become an instant success worldwide, winning several Toy of the Year awards, and becoming a staple of 1980's popular culture. To date, over 350 million Rubik's Cubes have been sold, making it one of the best selling toys of all time.<ref name=\"IBT\"/><ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/science/rubiks-cube-25-years-on-crazy-toys-crazy-times-5334529.html \"Rubik's Cube 25 years on: crazy toys, crazy times\"], ''Independent'', 15 August 2007.</ref>\n\n===Other inventions===\nIn addition to Rubik's Cube, Rubik is also the inventor of [[Rubik's Magic]], [[Rubik's Snake]] and [[Rubik's 360]] among others.<ref>{{cite web|title=Japan teen in historic Rubik win|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/7033519.stm|publisher=BBC News|date=8 October 2007|access-date=4 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Later career and other works===\nIn the early 1980s, he became the editor of a game and puzzle journal called ''..\u00c9s j\u00e1t\u00e9k'' (''...And games''), then became self-employed in 1983, founding the Rubik St\u00fadi\u00f3, where he designed furniture and games. In 1987 he became a professor with full tenure; in 1990 he became the president of the Hungarian Engineering Academy (''Magyar M\u00e9rn\u00f6ki Akad\u00e9mia''). At the Academy, he created the International Rubik Foundation to support especially talented young engineers and industrial designers.\n\nIn 2009, he was appointed as an honorary professor of [[Keimyung University]], Daegu, South Korea.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2017/07/178_52464.html|newspaper=The Korea Times|title=Cube Exhibition May Come to Korea|date=2009-09-24}}</ref>\n\n==Work and engagements in the 2010s==\nIn the 2010s, Rubik has recently spent much of his time working on ''Beyond Rubik's Cube'', a Science, Technology, Engineering, Mathematics ([[STEM fields]]) based exhibition, which will travel the globe over the next six years{{when|date=January 2020}}.<ref>[http://brc.lsc.org/ \"Beyond Rubik's Cube\"] Liberty Science Center, N.D. Retrieved 6 May 2014</ref> The grand opening of the exhibit was held on 26 April 2014 at the [[Liberty Science Center]] in New Jersey. At the exhibition, Rubik gave several lectures, tours, and engaged with the public and several members of the [[speedcubing]] crowd in attendance, including [[Anthony Michael Brooks]], a world-class speedcuber.<ref>Barron, James. [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/26/nyregion/rubiks-redux-a-colorful-cube-puzzles-anew.html?hpw&rref=nyregion \"A Cube With a Twist: At 40, It Puzzles Anew\"]. The New York Times, 25 April 2014. retrieved 6 May 2014</ref><ref>Matheson Whitney. [https://www.usatoday.com/story/popcandy/2014/04/25/rubiks-cube/8141175/ \"Forty years later, the Rubik's Cube still puzzles\"]. USA Today, 25 April 2014. Retrieved 6 May 2014</ref>\n\n==Influences==\nErn\u0151 Rubik has listed several individuals who, as he has said, \"exerted a great influence over me through their work.\" These include [[Leonardo da Vinci]], whom Rubik regards as ''the'' [[Renaissance man]]; [[Michelangelo]], whom he respects as a [[polymath]], painter, and sculptor; and artist [[M.C. Escher]], who drew impossible constructions and grappled with explorations of [[infinity]]. As regards to philosophers and writers, Rubik admires [[Voltaire]], [[Stendhal]], [[Thomas Mann]], [[Jean-Paul Sartre]], Hungarian poet [[Attila J\u00f3zsef]], [[Jules Verne]], and [[Isaac Asimov]]. In the field of architecture, Rubik is an admirer of [[Frank Lloyd Wright]] and [[Le Corbusier]].<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n\n==Cultural and leisure pursuits==\nRubik admits to being a lifelong bibliophile and has stated, \"Books offered me the possibility of gaining knowledge of the World, Nature and People.\" Rubik has stated that he has a special interest in science fiction.\n\nRubik is fond of outdoor activities such as walking through nature, playing sports, and sailing on [[Lake Balaton]]. Rubik is also an avid gardener and has stated that \"collecting succulents is my favourite pastime.\"<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n\n==Prizes and awards==\n* 1978 \u2013 Budapest International Trade Fair, Prize for the Cube<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\">[http://www.create2009.europa.eu/ambassadors/profiles/erno_rubik.html Europa Interview with Ern\u0151 Rubik] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328175740/http://www.create2009.europa.eu/ambassadors/profiles/erno_rubik.html |date=28 March 2016 }} Retrieved 5 May 2014</ref>\n* 1980 \u2013 Toy of the Year: Federal Republic of Germany, United Kingdom, France, USA<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n* 1981 \u2013 Toy of the Year: Finland, Sweden, Italy<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n* 1982 \u2013 Toy of the Year: United Kingdom (second time)<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n* 1982 \u2013 The Museum of Modern Art, New York selected Rubik's Cube into its permanent collection<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n* 1983 \u2013 Hungarian State Prize for demonstrating and teaching 3D structures and for the various solutions that inspired scientific researches in several ways<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n* 1988 \u2013 Juvenile Prize from the State Office of Youth and Sport<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n* 1995 \u2013 D\u00e9nes Gabor Prize from the Novofer Foundation as an acknowledgement of achievements in the field of innovation<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n* 1996 \u2013 \u00c1nyos Jedlik Prize from the Hungarian Patent Office<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n* 1997 \u2013 Prize for the Reputation of Hungary (1997)<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n* 2007 \u2013 [[Kossuth Prize]] the most prestigious cultural award in Hungary<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n* 2008 \u2013 Moholy-Nagy Prize \u2013 from the Moholy-Nagy University of Arts and Design<ref name=\"Rubik Interview\"/>\n* 2009 \u2013 EU Ambassador of the Year of Creativity and Innovation<ref>[http://www.create2009.europa.eu/press/news_archive/news_singleview/news/rubiks-cube-and-eu-politics-the-manifesto-for-creativity-and-innovation-in-europe.html Rubik's cube and EU Politics: The Manifesto for Creativity and Innovation in Europe Retrieved] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923211031/http://www.create2009.europa.eu/press/news_archive/news_singleview/news/rubiks-cube-and-eu-politics-the-manifesto-for-creativity-and-innovation-in-europe.html |date=23 September 2015 }} 5 May 2014</ref>\n* 2010 \u2013 USA Science and Engineering Festival Award (Outstanding Contribution to Science Education)<ref>[http://www.ait-budapest.com/news/ait-faculty-member-erno-rubik-is-honored-with-the-outstanding-contributions-to-science-educatio Ern\u0151 Rubik Awarded with the Outstanding Contributions to Science Education Award] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505072116/http://www.ait-budapest.com/news/ait-faculty-member-erno-rubik-is-honored-with-the-outstanding-contributions-to-science-educatio |date=5 May 2014 }} Retrieved 5 May 2014</ref>\n* 2010 \u2013 The Hungarian Order of Merit Commanders Cross with the Star\n* 2010 \u2013 Prima Primissima Prize\n* 2012 \u2013 My Country Awards\n* 2014 \u2013 Grand Cross of the Order of Saint Stephen (The highest medal awarded by Hungary)<ref>[http://www.daijiworld.com/news/news_disp.asp?n_id=257363 Ern\u0151 Rubik Awarded the Highest Medal Awarded by the country of Hungary] Retrieved 23 August 2014</ref>\n* 2014 \u2013 Honorary Citizen of Budapest<ref>[http://annyiversary.blogspot.hu/2014_07_01_archive.html Ern\u0151 Rubik Named as an Honorary Citizen of Budapest] Retrieved 23 August 2014</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nEditor and co-author of ''A b\u0171v\u00f6s kocka'' (\"The Magic Cube\"), M\u0171szaki Kiad\u00f3, Budapest, 1981.\n\nCo-author of ''The Rubik's Cube Compendium'' (written by David Singmaster, Ern\u0151 Rubik, Gerzson K\u00e9ri, Gy\u00f6rgy Marx, Tam\u00e1s Varga and Tam\u00e1s Vekerdy), Oxford University Press, 1987.<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/Rubiks-Cubic-Compendium-Recreations-Mathematics/dp/0198532024/ref=sr_1_2?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1399393012&sr=1-2 The Rubik\u2019s Cube Compendium]</ref>\n\n==Foundations and appearances==\nHe attended the 2007 World Championship in Budapest.<ref>John Nadler, [http://www.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,1669535,00.html \"Squaring Up to the Rubik's Cube\"], ''Time'', 9 October 2007.</ref><ref>[http://www.rubiks.com/~/media/Files/media_vault/Media%20folder_press_releases/July%202007%20%20%20%20Erno%20Rubik%20interview.ashx \"25 years on\"] Erno Rubik interview at the Rubik's Cube official website, retrieved 9 May 2010</ref> He also gave a lecture and autograph session at the \"Bridges-Pecs\" conference (\"Bridges between Mathematics and the Arts\") in July 2010.<ref>[http://bridgesmathart.org/bridges-2010/2010-plenary-speakers/ \"Bridges Conference\"] List of Plenary speakers, retrieved 26 July 2010</ref>\n\nRubik is a member of the [[USA Science and Engineering Festival]]'s Advisory Board.<ref>[http://www.usasciencefestival.org/about/advisors US Science and Engineering Festival Advisors] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100421005310/http://www.usasciencefestival.org/about/advisors/ |date=21 April 2010 }} Retrieved 2010-07-05.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://cubeland.free.fr/infos/ernorubik.htm An interview with Ern\u0151 Rubik]\n* [https://orszaginfo.magyarorszag.hu/informaciok/hiresmagyarok/rubikerno.html His biography at Hungary.hu] {{in lang|hu}}\n* [http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1874509,00.html His first print interview in ten years]\n* [http://www.time.com/rubik An exclusive video interview about the new Rubik's 360]\n\n{{Rubik's Cube}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rubik, Erno}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Budapest]]\n[[Category:Hungarian architects]]\n[[Category:Hungarian inventors]]\n[[Category:Recreational mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Puzzle designers]]\n[[Category:Rubik's Cube]]\n[[Category:Toy inventors]]\n", "name_user": "71.236.193.197", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePrizes and awards)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ern%C5%91_Rubik"}
{"title_page": "Ben Pomeroy", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name     = Ben Pomeroy\n|fullname       = Ben Pomeroy\n|nickname       = \n|image          = Ben Pomeroy 2.JPG \n|image_size     = 285px\n|caption        = \n|position       = {{Rlp|CE}}\n|birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1984|1|10|df=yes}}\n|birth_place   = [[Penrith, New South Wales|Penrith]], [[New South Wales, Australia]]\n|height         = {{convert|187|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|weight         = {{convert|96|kg|stlb|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.catalansdragons.com/equipe/|title=Catalans Dragons Equipe Saison 2015|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date=2015|website=Catalans Dragons site officiel|publisher= Catalans Dragons S.A.S.P.|access-date=25 June 2015}}</ref>\n|club1          = [[Penrith Panthers]]\n|year1start     = 2004\n|year1end       = 05\n|appearances1   = 10\n|tries1         = 2\n|goals1         = 0\n|fieldgoals1    = 0\n|points1        = 8\n|club2          = [[Cronulla-Sutherland Sharks|Cronulla Sharks]]\n|year2start     = 2006\n|year2end       = 13\n|appearances2   = 158\n|tries2         = 53\n|goals2         = 0\n|fieldgoals2    = 0\n|points2        = 188\n|club3          = [[Catalans Dragons]]\n|year3start     = 2014\n|year3end       = 15\n|appearances3   = 46\n|tries3         = 11\n|goals3         = 0\n|fieldgoals3    = 0 \n|points3        = 44\n|club4          = [[L\u00e9zignan Sangliers]]\n|year4start     = 2016\n|year4end       = 17\n|appearances4   = 18\n|tries4         = 14\n|goals4         = 0\n|fieldgoals4    = 0\n|points4        = 56\n|club5          = [[Warrington Wolves]]\n|year5start     = 2017\n|year5end       = \n|appearances5   = 4\n|tries5         = 4\n|goals5         = 0\n|fieldgoals5    = 0\n|points5        = 16\n|club6          = [[L\u00e9zignan Sangliers]]\n|year6start     = 2018\n|year6end       = \n|appearances6   = 4\n|tries6         = 0\n|goals6         = 0\n|fieldgoals6    = 0\n|points6        = 0\n|club7          = [[Warrington Wolves]]\n|year7start     = 2018\n|year7end       = \n|appearances7   = 8\n|tries7         = 0\n|goals7         = 0\n|fieldgoals7    = 0\n|points7        = 0\n|club8          = {{nowrap|\u2192 [[Rochdale Hornets]]}}\n|year8start     = 2018{{small|(loan)}}\n|year8end       = \n|appearances8   = 1\n|tries8         = 0\n|goals8         = 0\n|fieldgoals8    = 0\n|points8        = 0\n|club9          = [[Saint-Esteve XIII Catalan]]\n|year9start     = 2018\n|year9end       = 19\n|appearances9   = 11\n|tries9         = 6\n|goals9         = 0\n|fieldgoals9    = 0\n|points9        = 24\n|club10         = [[Palau XIII Broncos|Palau Broncos]]\n|year10start    = 2019\n|year10end      = present\n|appearances10  = 4\n|tries10        = 1\n|goals10        = 0\n|fieldgoals10   = 0 \n|points10       = 4\n|teamA          = [[City vs Country Origin|NSW City]]\n|yearAstart     = 2007\n|yearAend       = 09\n|appearancesA   = 3\n|triesA         = 1\n|goalsA         = 0\n|fieldgoalsA    = 0\n|pointsA        = 4\n|teamB          = [[Prime Minister's XIII]]\n|yearBstart     = 2007\n|yearBend       =\n|appearancesB   = 1\n|triesB         = 0\n|goalsB         = 0\n|fieldgoalsB    = 0\n|pointsB        = 0\n|retired        = \n|source         = <ref>[http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/players/Ben_Pomeroy/summary.html RLP]</ref><ref>[http://www.loverugbyleague.com/stats/players/Ben-Pomeroy/ Love Rugby League]</ref><ref>[http://www.itsrugby.co.uk/player_11370.html itsrugby]</ref>\n|updated        = 12 December 2019\n}}\n\n'''Ben Pomeroy''' (born 10 January 1984) is an Australian professional [[rugby league]] footballer who plays for the [[Saint-Esteve XIII Catalan]] in the [[Elite One Championship]]. He has played for [[Cambridge Park RLFC]] in the Penrith district then went on to play in the [[National Rugby League]] for Australian clubs, the [[Penrith Panthers]] and the [[Cronulla-Sutherland Sharks]], and in the [[Super League]] for the [[Catalans Dragons]] and [[L\u00e9zignan Sangliers]] in the [[Elite One Championship]]. His usual position is as a {{rlp|ce}}. He has been touted by such Rugby League commentators as Joshua Barratt and Daved Bonato as being the pretty alright.\n\n==Biography==\nPomeroy was born in [[Penrith, New South Wales]], Australia.\n\n===Playing career===\nPomeroy made his first grade debut for Penrith in round 21, of the [[2004 NRL season]]. After only sporadic NRL appearances for Penrith, Pomeroy signed with the [[Cronulla-Sutherland Sharks]] in 2006. A serious groin injury that year limited his appearances on the field for Cronulla to eight games. In 2007, he became a regular at centre in the run-on side and scored his first hat-trick of tries in Round 6.<ref>{{Cite news|publisher=Fairfax Digital LeagueHQ|title=Three in a row Pomeroy|url=http://www.leaguehq.com.au/news/lhqmatchreport/three-in-a-row-pomeroy/2007/04/21/1176697156833.html|accessdate=23 December 2007|date=22 April 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070905023107/http://www.leaguehq.com.au/news/lhqmatchreport/three-in-a-row-pomeroy/2007/04/21/1176697156833.html|archivedate=5 September 2007 }}</ref> \n[[File:Ben Pomeroy, Erin.jpg|thumb|right|Pomeroy at the [[2012 Dally M Awards]]]]\n\nIn the [[2008 NRL season]], Pomeroy played 26 games for Cronulla as the club reached the preliminary final against [[Melbourne Storm|Melbourne]] but were defeated 28-0 at the [[Sydney Football Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mobile.abc.net.au/news/2008-09-27/storm-through-to-nrl-final/523884/|title=Storm through to NRL final|website=ABC}}</ref>  \n\nPomeroy played with Cronulla up until the end of the [[2013 NRL season]].  His final game for the club was the elimination semi-final against [[Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles|Manly-Warringah]] which Cronulla lost 24-18.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/sharks-and-sea-eagles-bitter-rivarly-four-decades-in-the-making/news-story/6326c674f313f35f5dcc13505893e490|title=Sharks and Sea Eagles Bitter Rivalry Four Decades in the Making|website=Dailytelegraph.com.au|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nPomeroy was highly regarded at the club for being one of the most consistent players during Cronulla's poor run of form from 2009 - 2012. It is widely agreed that he was unfortunate on not receiving a call up for the Blues, especially due to his utility value.\n\nPomeroy was signed by [[Catalans Dragons]] ahead of the 2014 [[Super League]] season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Super League: Catalan (sic) Dragons sign Aussie centre Ben Pomeroy for 2014 season|url=http://www.skysports.com/rugby-league/news/12216/8978998/super-league-catalan-dragons-sign-aussie-centre-ben-pomeroy-for-2014-season|website=Sky Sports|accessdate=28 February 2016|date=18 October 2013}}</ref> In 2015, he was sent off in two consecutive home games against [[St Helens R.F.C.|St. Helens]] and [[Castleford Tigers]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=de Menezes|first1=Jack|title=Ben Pomeroy tackle: Catalan (sic) Dragons centre sent-off for WWE-style suplex on Ashley Gibson during win over Castleford|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/rugby-league/ben-pomeroy-tackle-video-catalan-dragons-centre-sent-off-for-wwe-style-suplex-on-ashley-gibson-10469136.html|website=The Independent|accessdate=28 February 2016|date=24 August 2015}}</ref> the latter of which resulted in a six-game suspension for a dangerous tackle on [[Ashley Gibson]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ben Pomeroy: Catalans Dragons centre banned for six games|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/34056885|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=28 February 2016|date=25 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nPomeroy was one of seventeen Cronulla-Sutherland players found guilty of using illegal substances under the club's [[Cronulla-Sutherland Sharks supplements saga|2011 supplements program]], having a twelve-month suspension (which had already expired due to backdating) recorded against his name.<ref name=\"forgottenfivepenalties\">{{cite web|url=https://au.sports.yahoo.com/league/a/32885375/sharks-finalise-asada-deal/#page1|title=Sharks finalise ASADA deal|publisher=Yahoo!7|first=Steve|last=Zemek|date=13 October 2016|accessdate=13 October 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161013150138/https://au.sports.yahoo.com/league/a/32885375/sharks-finalise-asada-deal/#page1|archivedate=13 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Representative career===\nPomeroy was selected on the bench for [[City vs Country Origin|City Origin]] in 2007 and was also named in the City side in 2008. Later this same year, his successful season was rewarded with selection in the [[Prime Minister's XIII]] side to play the Papua New Guinea [[Papua New Guinea national rugby league team|Kumuls]].<ref>{{Cite news|publisher=The Western Australian|title=Trio called up for PM's XIII side|url=http://www.thewest.com.au/aapstory.aspx?StoryName=418293|accessdate=23 December 2007|date=13 September 2007}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Assault charge===\nPomeroy was charged with [[assault|assault occasioning actual bodily harm]] after allegedly punching a fellow concert-goer in the face during a performance by American rock band [[Korn]] at the [[Sydney Entertainment Centre]] on 20 April 2008. The charges were later dismissed due to a lack of evidence.<ref>{{Cite news|publisher=The Courier-Mail|title=Ben Pomeroy assault case dropped, not enough evidence|url=http://www.news.com.au/couriermail/story/0,,24817700-5003409,00.html|accessdate=21 May 2009|date=18 December 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Career highlights==\n* ''First Grade Debut:'' 2004 - Round 21, Penrith vs [[Bulldogs (NRL team)|Canterbury-Bankstown]] at [[Telstra Stadium]], 30 July\n*  ''First Hitpass:'' 2004 - Round 23, Penrith vs [[Sydney Roosters]], 13 August. Shane Cornford rated it as the third best he\u2019d ever seen.\n* ''First Hat-trick:'' 2007 - Round 6, Cronulla-Sutherland vs [[Canberra Raiders]] at [[Canberra Stadium]], 21 April, scoring three tries in a fourteen-minute period\n* ''Representative Selection:'' 2007 - City vs Country at [[Coffs Harbour]], 3 May\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist|40em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060821104345/http://www.sharks.com.au/index.php?id=103 Official player profile]\n*[http://www.nrl.com/Clubs/Sharks/SharksPlayerProfile/tabid/234/playerid/43/Default.aspx NRL player profile]{{dead link|date=October 2016|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pomeroy, Ben}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian rugby league players]]\n[[Category:Catalans Dragons players]]\n[[Category:Cronulla-Sutherland Sharks players]]\n[[Category:L\u00e9zignan Sangliers players]]\n[[Category:New South Wales City Origin rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Penrith Panthers players]]\n[[Category:Prime Minister's XIII players]]\n[[Category:Rugby league centres]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name     = Ben Pomeroy\n|fullname       = Ben Pomeroy\n|nickname       = \n|image          = Ben Pomeroy 2.JPG \n|image_size     = 285px\n|caption        = \n|position       = {{Rlp|CE}}\n|birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1984|1|10|df=yes}}\n|birth_place   = [[Penrith, New South Wales|Penrith]], [[New South Wales, Australia]]\n|height         = {{convert|187|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|weight         = {{convert|96|kg|stlb|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.catalansdragons.com/equipe/|title=Catalans Dragons Equipe Saison 2015|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date=2015|website=Catalans Dragons site officiel|publisher= Catalans Dragons S.A.S.P.|access-date=25 June 2015}}</ref>\n|club1          = [[Penrith Panthers]]\n|year1start     = 2004\n|year1end       = 05\n|appearances1   = 10\n|tries1         = 2\n|goals1         = 0\n|fieldgoals1    = 0\n|points1        = 8\n|club2          = [[Cronulla-Sutherland Sharks|Cronulla Sharks]]\n|year2start     = 2006\n|year2end       = 13\n|appearances2   = 158\n|tries2         = 53\n|goals2         = 0\n|fieldgoals2    = 0\n|points2        = 188\n|club3          = [[Catalans Dragons]]\n|year3start     = 2014\n|year3end       = 15\n|appearances3   = 46\n|tries3         = 11\n|goals3         = 0\n|fieldgoals3    = 0 \n|points3        = 44\n|club4          = [[L\u00e9zignan Sangliers]]\n|year4start     = 2016\n|year4end       = 17\n|appearances4   = 18\n|tries4         = 14\n|goals4         = 0\n|fieldgoals4    = 0\n|points4        = 56\n|club5          = [[Warrington Wolves]]\n|year5start     = 2017\n|year5end       = \n|appearances5   = 4\n|tries5         = 4\n|goals5         = 0\n|fieldgoals5    = 0\n|points5        = 16\n|club6          = [[L\u00e9zignan Sangliers]]\n|year6start     = 2018\n|year6end       = \n|appearances6   = 4\n|tries6         = 0\n|goals6         = 0\n|fieldgoals6    = 0\n|points6        = 0\n|club7          = [[Warrington Wolves]]\n|year7start     = 2018\n|year7end       = \n|appearances7   = 8\n|tries7         = 0\n|goals7         = 0\n|fieldgoals7    = 0\n|points7        = 0\n|club8          = {{nowrap|\u2192 [[Rochdale Hornets]]}}\n|year8start     = 2018{{small|(loan)}}\n|year8end       = \n|appearances8   = 1\n|tries8         = 0\n|goals8         = 0\n|fieldgoals8    = 0\n|points8        = 0\n|club9          = [[Saint-Esteve XIII Catalan]]\n|year9start     = 2018\n|year9end       = 19\n|appearances9   = 11\n|tries9         = 6\n|goals9         = 0\n|fieldgoals9    = 0\n|points9        = 24\n|club10         = [[Palau XIII Broncos|Palau Broncos]]\n|year10start    = 2019\n|year10end      = present\n|appearances10  = 4\n|tries10        = 1\n|goals10        = 0\n|fieldgoals10   = 0 \n|points10       = 4\n|teamA          = [[City vs Country Origin|NSW City]]\n|yearAstart     = 2007\n|yearAend       = 09\n|appearancesA   = 3\n|triesA         = 1\n|goalsA         = 0\n|fieldgoalsA    = 0\n|pointsA        = 4\n|teamB          = [[Prime Minister's XIII]]\n|yearBstart     = 2007\n|yearBend       =\n|appearancesB   = 1\n|triesB         = 0\n|goalsB         = 0\n|fieldgoalsB    = 0\n|pointsB        = 0\n|retired        = \n|source         = <ref>[http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/players/Ben_Pomeroy/summary.html RLP]</ref><ref>[http://www.loverugbyleague.com/stats/players/Ben-Pomeroy/ Love Rugby League]</ref><ref>[http://www.itsrugby.co.uk/player_11370.html itsrugby]</ref>\n|updated        = 12 December 2019\n}}\n\n'''Ben Pomeroy''' (born 10 January 1984) is an Australian professional [[rugby league]] footballer who plays for the [[Saint-Esteve XIII Catalan]] in the [[Elite One Championship]]. He has played for [[Cambridge Park RLFC]] in the Penrith district then went on to play in the [[National Rugby League]] for Australian clubs, the [[Penrith Panthers]] and the [[Cronulla-Sutherland Sharks]], and in the [[Super League]] for the [[Catalans Dragons]] and [[FC Lezignan]] in the [[Elite One Championship]]. His usual position is as a {{rlp|ce}}. He has been touted by such Rugby League commentators as Joshua Barratt and Daved Bonato as being the pretty alright.\n\n==Biography==\nPomeroy was born in [[Penrith, New South Wales]], Australia.\n\n===Playing career===\nPomeroy made his first grade debut for Penrith in round 21, of the [[2004 NRL season]]. After only sporadic NRL appearances for Penrith, Pomeroy signed with the [[Cronulla-Sutherland Sharks]] in 2006. A serious groin injury that year limited his appearances on the field for Cronulla to eight games. In 2007, he became a regular at centre in the run-on side and scored his first hat-trick of tries in Round 6.<ref>{{Cite news|publisher=Fairfax Digital LeagueHQ|title=Three in a row Pomeroy|url=http://www.leaguehq.com.au/news/lhqmatchreport/three-in-a-row-pomeroy/2007/04/21/1176697156833.html|accessdate=23 December 2007|date=22 April 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070905023107/http://www.leaguehq.com.au/news/lhqmatchreport/three-in-a-row-pomeroy/2007/04/21/1176697156833.html|archivedate=5 September 2007 }}</ref> \n[[File:Ben Pomeroy, Erin.jpg|thumb|right|Pomeroy at the [[2012 Dally M Awards]]]]\n\nIn the [[2008 NRL season]], Pomeroy played 26 games for Cronulla as the club reached the preliminary final against [[Melbourne Storm|Melbourne]] but were defeated 28-0 at the [[Sydney Football Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mobile.abc.net.au/news/2008-09-27/storm-through-to-nrl-final/523884/|title=Storm through to NRL final|website=ABC}}</ref>  \n\nPomeroy played with Cronulla up until the end of the [[2013 NRL season]].  His final game for the club was the elimination semi-final against [[Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles|Manly-Warringah]] which Cronulla lost 24-18.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/sharks-and-sea-eagles-bitter-rivarly-four-decades-in-the-making/news-story/6326c674f313f35f5dcc13505893e490|title=Sharks and Sea Eagles Bitter Rivalry Four Decades in the Making|website=Dailytelegraph.com.au|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nPomeroy was highly regarded at the club for being one of the most consistent players during Cronulla's poor run of form from 2009 - 2012. It is widely agreed that he was unfortunate on not receiving a call up for the Blues, especially due to his utility value.\n\nPomeroy was signed by [[Catalans Dragons]] ahead of the 2014 [[Super League]] season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Super League: Catalan (sic) Dragons sign Aussie centre Ben Pomeroy for 2014 season|url=http://www.skysports.com/rugby-league/news/12216/8978998/super-league-catalan-dragons-sign-aussie-centre-ben-pomeroy-for-2014-season|website=Sky Sports|accessdate=28 February 2016|date=18 October 2013}}</ref> In 2015, he was sent off in two consecutive home games against [[St Helens R.F.C.|St. Helens]] and [[Castleford Tigers]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=de Menezes|first1=Jack|title=Ben Pomeroy tackle: Catalan (sic) Dragons centre sent-off for WWE-style suplex on Ashley Gibson during win over Castleford|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/rugby-league/ben-pomeroy-tackle-video-catalan-dragons-centre-sent-off-for-wwe-style-suplex-on-ashley-gibson-10469136.html|website=The Independent|accessdate=28 February 2016|date=24 August 2015}}</ref> the latter of which resulted in a six-game suspension for a dangerous tackle on [[Ashley Gibson]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ben Pomeroy: Catalans Dragons centre banned for six games|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/34056885|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=28 February 2016|date=25 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nPomeroy was one of seventeen Cronulla-Sutherland players found guilty of using illegal substances under the club's [[Cronulla-Sutherland Sharks supplements saga|2011 supplements program]], having a twelve-month suspension (which had already expired due to backdating) recorded against his name.<ref name=\"forgottenfivepenalties\">{{cite web|url=https://au.sports.yahoo.com/league/a/32885375/sharks-finalise-asada-deal/#page1|title=Sharks finalise ASADA deal|publisher=Yahoo!7|first=Steve|last=Zemek|date=13 October 2016|accessdate=13 October 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161013150138/https://au.sports.yahoo.com/league/a/32885375/sharks-finalise-asada-deal/#page1|archivedate=13 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Representative career===\nPomeroy was selected on the bench for [[City vs Country Origin|City Origin]] in 2007 and was also named in the City side in 2008. Later this same year, his successful season was rewarded with selection in the [[Prime Minister's XIII]] side to play the Papua New Guinea [[Papua New Guinea national rugby league team|Kumuls]].<ref>{{Cite news|publisher=The Western Australian|title=Trio called up for PM's XIII side|url=http://www.thewest.com.au/aapstory.aspx?StoryName=418293|accessdate=23 December 2007|date=13 September 2007}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Assault charge===\nPomeroy was charged with [[assault|assault occasioning actual bodily harm]] after allegedly punching a fellow concert-goer in the face during a performance by American rock band [[Korn]] at the [[Sydney Entertainment Centre]] on 20 April 2008. The charges were later dismissed due to a lack of evidence.<ref>{{Cite news|publisher=The Courier-Mail|title=Ben Pomeroy assault case dropped, not enough evidence|url=http://www.news.com.au/couriermail/story/0,,24817700-5003409,00.html|accessdate=21 May 2009|date=18 December 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Career highlights==\n* ''First Grade Debut:'' 2004 - Round 21, Penrith vs [[Bulldogs (NRL team)|Canterbury-Bankstown]] at [[Telstra Stadium]], 30 July\n*  ''First Hitpass:'' 2004 - Round 23, Penrith vs [[Sydney Roosters]], 13 August. Shane Cornford rated it as the third best he\u2019d ever seen.\n* ''First Hat-trick:'' 2007 - Round 6, Cronulla-Sutherland vs [[Canberra Raiders]] at [[Canberra Stadium]], 21 April, scoring three tries in a fourteen-minute period\n* ''Representative Selection:'' 2007 - City vs Country at [[Coffs Harbour]], 3 May\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist|40em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060821104345/http://www.sharks.com.au/index.php?id=103 Official player profile]\n*[http://www.nrl.com/Clubs/Sharks/SharksPlayerProfile/tabid/234/playerid/43/Default.aspx NRL player profile]{{dead link|date=October 2016|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pomeroy, Ben}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian rugby league players]]\n[[Category:Catalans Dragons players]]\n[[Category:Cronulla-Sutherland Sharks players]]\n[[Category:L\u00e9zignan Sangliers players]]\n[[Category:New South Wales City Origin rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Penrith Panthers players]]\n[[Category:Prime Minister's XIII players]]\n[[Category:Rugby league centres]]\n", "name_user": "Jmg38", "label": "safe", "comment": "use same link throughout", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ben_Pomeroy"}
{"title_page": "Jocelyn Lee (actress)", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Jocelyn Lee\n| image         = Jocelyn Lee - May 1922 Tatler.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Mary Alice Simpson\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1902|6|21}}\n| birth_place   = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1980|6|15|1902|6|21}}\n| death_place   = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| occupation    = Actress\n| other_names = Jocelyn Leigh\n| years_active  =\n| spouse        = {{Marriage|[[Henry Lehrman]]|1922|1924|end=div.}}<br>{{Marriage|[[Luther Reed]]|1930|1931|end=div.}}<br>{{Marriage|James Seymour|1935|1976|end=d.}}\n}}\n\n'''Jocelyn Lee''' (born '''Mary Alice Simpson''';<ref name=\"dn\">{{cite news |title=Lehrman, Ex-Fiance of Virginia Rappe, Marries |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24838533/daily_news/ |work=Daily News |date=April 29, 1922 |location=New York, New York City |page=27|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = October 25, 2018}} {{Open access}}</ref> June 21, 1902 \u2013 June 15, 1980) was an American actress. She was also known as '''Jocelyn Leigh.'''<ref name=\"dn\" />\n\nFilms in which Lee appeared included ''[[Paris at Midnight]]'', ''[[Sunny Side Up (1926 film)|Sunny Side Up]]'', ''[[The Campus Flirt]]'', ''[[Everybody's Acting]]'', ''[[A Kiss in a Taxi]]'', ''[[Afraid to Love]]'', ''[[The Love Thrill]]'', ''[[Say It with Diamonds (1927 film)|Say It with Diamonds]]'', ''[[Ten Modern Commandments]]'', ''[[Shanghai Bound]]'', ''[[The Masked Angel]]'', ''[[The Night Bird]]'', ''[[Dry Martini (1928 film)|Dry Martini]]'', ''[[Broadway Babies]]'', ''[[Twin Beds (1929 film)|Twin Beds]]'', ''[[The Love Trap (1929 film)|The Love Trap]]'', ''[[Three Live Ghosts (1929 film)|Three Live Ghosts]]'', ''[[Young Nowheres]]'', ''[[The Marriage Playground]]'', ''[[No, No, Nanette (1930 film)|No, No, Nanette]]'' and ''[[Her First Mate]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmovie.com/artist/jocelyn-lee-p41422 |title=Jocelyn Lee |publisher=AllMovie |date= |accessdate=2018-10-21}}</ref>\n\nLee also performed in the ''[[Ziegfeld Follies]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |title=(photo caption) |journal=The Tatler |date=May 1922 |volume=4 |issue=4 |page=3 |url=https://archive.org/details/TatlerMay1922/page/n3 |accessdate=25 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn April 27, 1922, Lee married film producer [[Henry Lehrman]] in Los Angeles.<ref name=dn/> They were divorced on December 16, 1924.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Walker |first1=Brent E. |title=Mack Sennett's Fun Factory: A History and Filmography of His Studio and His Keystone and Mack Sennett Comedies, with Biographies of Players and Personnel |date=2013 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=9780786477111 |page=572 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x_icAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA572&dq=%22Jocelyn+Leigh%22+actress&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiU84b1pqLeAhXG3lMKHQM0AVkQ6AEIUjAI#v=onepage&q=%22Jocelyn%20Leigh%22%20actress&f=false |accessdate=25 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref> She later married director and writer [[Luther Reed]]; they were divorced on April 3, 1931.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jocelyn Lee, of Films, Divorces Luther Reed |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24840000/jocelyn_lee/ |work=The Philadelphia Inquirer |agency=Associated Press |date=April 4, 1931 |location=Pennsylvania, Philadelphia |page=3|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = October 25, 2018}} {{Open access}}</ref> In January 1935, Lee married associate producer James Seymour.<ref>{{cite news |title=Busy Week-end for Cupid in Hollywood |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24840222/the_boston_globe/ |work=The Boston Globe |agency=Associated Press |date=January 14, 1936 |location=Massachusetts, Boston |page=23|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = October 25, 2018}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0497547}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lee, Jocelyn}}\n[[Category:1902 births]]\n[[Category:1980 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-