{"title_page": "October 2010 Arizona tornado outbreak", "text_new": "{{Infobox storm\n| name = October 2010 Arizona tornado outbreak\n| image = October 6, 2010 Bellemont, Arizona tornado damage.jpg\n| caption = A home damaged by an EF2 tornado in [[Bellemont, Arizona]]\n| type = Tornado outbreak\n| active = October 6, 2010 \n| lowest pressure = \n| lowest temperature =\n| tornadoes = 9 confirmed\n| fujitascale = EF3\n| enhanced = yes\n| tornado duration = 1:58&nbsp;a.m.&nbsp;\u2013 1:05&nbsp;p.m. [[Mountain Standard Time|MST]] (11 hours, 57 minutes)\n| highest winds = \n| gusts =\n| hail =  <!-- unused? -->\n| maximum snow = \n| damages = $2.81 billion from Hail, $1.6 million from Bellemont Tornadoes\n| power outages =\n| affected = \n| current advisories =\n| notes = \n| alt = \n| fatalities =  None reported (11 injuries)\n}} \nThe '''October 2010 Arizona tornado outbreak''' was the largest single-day [[tornado]]-event in [[Arizona]] history, with nine tornadoes touching down.\n\n==Meteorological synopsis==\nOn October&nbsp;5 and 6, 2010, a strong [[Low pressure area|area of low pressure]] situated off the coast of [[California]] produced a southerly flow of warm, moist air into [[Arizona]]. Warm surface temperatures and clear skies throughout the day on October 5 allowed for significant [[Atmospheric instability|instability]], resulting in scattered [[severe thunderstorm]]s during the late afternoon, evening and overnight hours. These storms produced widespread damaging [[hail]], ranging up to {{convert|3.0|in|cm|abbr=on}} in diameter, and [[tropical cyclone|hurricane]]-force wind gusts of {{convert|86|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}. Throughout the [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]] Metropolitan Area, {{convert|2|in|cm|abbr=on}} hail caused considerable damage to hundreds of  thousands of structures.  A tornado watch was issued by the Storm Prediction Center earlier that day.  Tornado Warnings were issued during the evening and overnight/early morning hours by the local NWS offices in Phoenix and Flagstaff when strong rotation was visible within the t-storms on radar.\n\n9 confirmed tornadoes were reported by the Flagstaff office of the National Weather Service.\n\n==Confirmed tornadoes==\n{{Tornado Chart\n|Total = 8\n|F0 = 2\n|F1 = 1\n|F2 = 4\n|F3 = 1\n|F4 = 0\n|F5 = 0\n|Enhanced=yes\n}}\n\n===October 6 event===\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible\" width=\"100%\"\n!colspan=\"7\"|List of reported tornadoes - Wednesday, October 6, 2010\n|-\n|<center>'''[[Enhanced Fujita scale|EF#]]'''</center> || <center>'''Location'''</center> || <center>'''County'''</center> || <center>'''Coord.'''</center> || <center>'''Time (UTC)'''</center> || <center>'''Path length'''</center> || <center>'''Comments/Damage'''</center>\n|-\n|colspan=\"7\" align=center|'''[[Arizona]]'''\n|-\n|bgcolor=#{{storm colour|cat1}} | <big>'''EF1'''</big>\n|'''NE of [[Clint's Well, Arizona|Clint's Well]]'''\n|[[Coconino County, Arizona|Coconino]]\n|{{Coord|34.483|-111.29|name=Clint's Well (Oct. 6, EF1)}}\n|0858\n|{{convert|14.06|mi|km|}}\n|Many trees were knocked down with several forest roads blocked.\n|-\n|bgcolor=#{{storm colour|cat2}} | <big>'''EF2'''</big>\n|'''[[Bellemont, Arizona|Bellemont]] area''' (1st tornado)\n|[[Coconino County, Arizona|Coconino]]\n|{{Coord|34.9863|-111.871|name=Bellemont (Oct. 6, EF2)}}\n|1153\n|{{convert|34.14|mi|km|}}\n|Unusually long-lived tornado remained on the ground for 51&nbsp;minutes along a path {{convert|34.14|mi|km|abbr=on}} long, ranking it as the longest tracked tornado in Arizona history. Over 100 houses and several businesses were damaged, including at least 21 houses that were destroyed. Massive tree damage was also reported with thousands of trees snapped, and campers isolated as a result. An RV dealer was impacted, with many vehicles destroyed. Seven people were injured.\n|-\n|bgcolor=#{{storm colour|cat2}} | <big>'''EF2'''</big>\n|'''[[Bellemont, Arizona|Bellemont]] area''' (2nd tornado)\n|[[Coconino County, Arizona|Coconino]]\n|{{Coord|34.9976|-111.877|name=Bellemont (Oct. 6, EF2)}}\n|1254\n|{{convert|32.02|mi|km|}}\n|Long track (second longest in the state's history), large wedge tornado derailed a train and damaged 28 rail cars. Forest damage was severe and many roads were blocked, and thousands of trees snapped. Power poles were also snapped.\n|-\n|bgcolor=#{{storm colour|cat2}} | <big>'''EF2'''</big>\n|'''S of [[Bellemont, Arizona|Bellemont]]'''\n|[[Coconino County, Arizona|Coconino]]\n|{{Coord|34.9824|-111.927|name=Bellemont (Oct. 6, EF2)}}\n|1350\n|{{convert|18.55|mi|km|}}\n|Tornado remained in forested areas with severe tree damage.\n|-\n|bgcolor=#{{storm colour|cat2}} | <big>'''EF2'''</big>\n|'''NNW of [[Sedona Airport]]'''\n|[[Coconino County, Arizona|Coconino]]\n|{{Coord|34.981|-111.876|name=Kachina (Oct. 6, EF2)}}\n|1610\n|{{convert|2.77|mi|km|}}\n|Significant tree damage in the area.\n|-\n|bgcolor=#{{storm colour|storm}} | <big>'''EF0'''</big>\n|'''SE of [[Cordes Lakes, Arizona|Cordes Lakes]]'''\n|[[Yavapai County, Arizona|Yavapai]]\n|{{Coord|34.1358|-112.055|name=Cordes Lakes(Oct. 6, EF0)}}\n|1730\n|{{convert|7.26|mi|km|}}\n|Tornado remained over grasslands east of [[Interstate 17]].\n|-\n|bgcolor=#{{storm colour|cat3}} | <big>'''EF3'''</big>\n|'''SE of [[Tuba City, Arizona|Tuba City]]'''\n|[[Coconino County, Arizona|Coconino]]\n|{{Coord|35.9342|-111.001|name=Tuba City (Oct. 6, EF3)}}\n|1905\n|unknown\n|Very large tornado, estimated at {{convert|0.625|mi|km|abbr=on}} wide, tracked over an unpopulated region. Three metal [[truss]] [[transmission tower]]s were destroyed - one of which was flattened - on the [[Navajo Nation]]. Aside from this, no other damage took place and a track could not be determined as the area covered by the tornado was remote wilderness. This was one of three F3/EF3 tornadoes in the state since 1950.\n|-\n|bgcolor=#{{storm colour|storm}} | <big>'''EF0'''</big>\n|'''S of [[Munds Park, Arizona|Munds Park]]'''\n|[[Coconino County, Arizona|Coconino]]\n|{{Coord|34.9404|-111.665|name=Munds Park (Oct. 6, EF0)}}\n|1905\n|{{convert|17.05|mi|km|}}\n|Tornado visually observed in several locations with minimal damage. Houses sustained damage to windows and siding.\n|-\n|colspan=\"7\" align=center|'''[[Utah]]'''\n|-\n|bgcolor=#{{storm colour|storm}} | <big>'''EF0'''</big>\n|'''WSW of [[Canyonlands National Park]]'''\n|[[Wayne County, Utah|Wayne]]\n|{{Coord|38.28|-110.28|name=Canyonlands (Oct. 6, EF0)}}\n|2000\n|{{convert|1.24|mi|km|}}\n|About 30 juniper trees were snapped or uprooted in a remote forested area.\n|-\n|colspan=\"7\" | <small>Sources: [http://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/101006_rpts.html SPC Storm Reports for 10/06/10], [http://www.wrh.noaa.gov/fgz/News/06Oct2010tor/06Oct2010.html NWS Flagstaff], [http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~storms NCDC Storm Data]</small>\n|}\n\n==Hailstorms==\nPrior to the tornado outbreak, widespread [[hail]] impacted the Phoenix metropolitan area. Three supercells caused considerable hail damage to over 150,000 homes<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://archive.azcentral.com/business/articles/20111003weather-phoenix-hail-damage-disputes.html|title=After 2010 Phoenix-area hailstorm, damage and disputes|newspaper=Arizona Republic|access-date=2017-02-09}}</ref> in Phoenix, Glendale, Peoria, Mesa and Scottsdale. In some instances, record or near-record-sized hailstones were measured and the largest stone reached {{convert|3.0|in|cm|abbr=on}} in diameter.<ref name=\"NWSFlagstaff\">{{cite web|work=National Weather Service in Flagstaff, Arizona|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=October 12, 2010|accessdate=June 22, 2011|title=Tornado Outbreak Strikes Northern Arizona|url=http://www.wrh.noaa.gov/fgz/News/06Oct2010tor/06Oct2010.html}}</ref> Overall, the hail caused $2.81 billion in damage in 2010 Dollars and injured one person.<ref name=\"NCDC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|year=2010|publisher=National Climatic Data Center|accessdate=February 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Tornadoes of 2010]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Lx4TUg3TD-s Video of the hailstorm in Phoenix]\n\n{{2010 tornado outbreaks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2010-10-06 Arizona tornado outbreak}}\n[[Category:F3 tornadoes by date]]\n[[Category:F3 tornadoes by location|Arizona]]\n[[Category:Tornado outbreaks]]\n[[Category:2010 natural disasters in the United States|Tornado,2010-10-06,Arizona]]\n[[Category:2010 in Arizona]]\n[[Category:October 2010 events in the United States|Arizona tornado outbreak]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox storm\n| name = October 2010 Arizona tornado outbreak\n| image = October 6, 2010 Bellemont, Arizona tornado damage.jpg\n| caption = A home damaged by an EF2 tornado in [[Bellemont, Arizona]]\n| type = Tornado outbreak\n| active = October 6, 2010 \n| lowest pressure = \n| lowest temperature =\n| tornadoes = 9 confirmed\n| fujitascale = EF3\n| enhanced = yes\n| tornado duration = 1:58&nbsp;a.m.&nbsp;\u2013 1:05&nbsp;p.m. [[Mountain Standard Time|MST]] (11 hours, 57 minutes)\n| highest winds = \n| gusts =\n| hail =  <!-- unused? -->\n| maximum snow = \n| damages = $2.81 billion from Hail, $1.6 million from Bellemont Tornadoes\n| power outages =\n| affected = \n| current advisories =\n| notes = \n| alt = \n| fatalities =  None reported (11 injuries)\n}} \nThe '''October 2010 Arizona tornado outbreak''' was the largest single-day [[tornado]]-event in [[Arizona]] history, with nine tornadoes touching down.\n\n==Meteorological synopsis==\nOn October&nbsp;5 and 6, 2010, a strong [[Low pressure area|area of low pressure]] situated off the coast of [[California]] produced a southerly flow of warm, moist air into [[Arizona]]. Warm surface temperatures and clear skies throughout the day on October 5 allowed for significant [[Atmospheric instability|instability]], resulting in scattered [[severe thunderstorm]]s during the late afternoon, evening and overnight hours. These storms produced widespread damaging [[hail]], ranging up to {{convert|3.0|in|cm|abbr=on}} in diameter, and [[tropical cyclone|hurricane]]-force wind gusts of {{convert|86|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}. Throughout the [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]] Metropolitan Area, {{convert|2|in|cm|abbr=on}} hail caused considerable damage to hundreds of  thousands of structures.  A tornado watch was issued by the Storm Prediction Center earlier that day.  Tornado Warnings were issued during the evening and overnight/early morning hours by the local NWS offices in Phoenix and Flagstaff when strong rotation was visible within the t-storms on radar.\n\n9 confirmed tornadoes were reported by the Flagstaff office of the National Weather Service.\n\n==Confirmed tornadoes==\n{{Tornado Chart\n|Total = 9\n|F0 = 2\n|F1 = 1\n|F2 = 4\n|F3 = 1\n|F4 = 0\n|F5 = 0\n|Enhanced=yes\n}}\n\n===October 6 event===\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible\" width=\"100%\"\n!colspan=\"7\"|List of reported tornadoes - Wednesday, October 6, 2010\n|-\n|<center>'''[[Enhanced Fujita scale|EF#]]'''</center> || <center>'''Location'''</center> || <center>'''County'''</center> || <center>'''Coord.'''</center> || <center>'''Time (UTC)'''</center> || <center>'''Path length'''</center> || <center>'''Comments/Damage'''</center>\n|-\n|colspan=\"7\" align=center|'''[[Arizona]]'''\n|-\n|bgcolor=#{{storm colour|cat1}} | <big>'''EF1'''</big>\n|'''NE of [[Clint's Well, Arizona|Clint's Well]]'''\n|[[Coconino County, Arizona|Coconino]]\n|{{Coord|34.483|-111.29|name=Clint's Well (Oct. 6, EF1)}}\n|0858\n|{{convert|14.06|mi|km|}}\n|Many trees were knocked down with several forest roads blocked.\n|-\n|bgcolor=#{{storm colour|cat2}} | <big>'''EF2'''</big>\n|'''[[Bellemont, Arizona|Bellemont]] area''' (1st tornado)\n|[[Coconino County, Arizona|Coconino]]\n|{{Coord|34.9863|-111.871|name=Bellemont (Oct. 6, EF2)}}\n|1153\n|{{convert|34.14|mi|km|}}\n|Unusually long-lived tornado remained on the ground for 51&nbsp;minutes along a path {{convert|34.14|mi|km|abbr=on}} long, ranking it as the longest tracked tornado in Arizona history. Over 100 houses and several businesses were damaged, including at least 21 houses that were destroyed. Massive tree damage was also reported with thousands of trees snapped, and campers isolated as a result. An RV dealer was impacted, with many vehicles destroyed. Seven people were injured.\n|-\n|bgcolor=#{{storm colour|cat2}} | <big>'''EF2'''</big>\n|'''[[Bellemont, Arizona|Bellemont]] area''' (2nd tornado)\n|[[Coconino County, Arizona|Coconino]]\n|{{Coord|34.9976|-111.877|name=Bellemont (Oct. 6, EF2)}}\n|1254\n|{{convert|32.02|mi|km|}}\n|Long track (second longest in the state's history), large wedge tornado derailed a train and damaged 28 rail cars. Forest damage was severe and many roads were blocked, and thousands of trees snapped. Power poles were also snapped.\n|-\n|bgcolor=#{{storm colour|cat2}} | <big>'''EF2'''</big>\n|'''S of [[Bellemont, Arizona|Bellemont]]'''\n|[[Coconino County, Arizona|Coconino]]\n|{{Coord|34.9824|-111.927|name=Bellemont (Oct. 6, EF2)}}\n|1350\n|{{convert|18.55|mi|km|}}\n|Tornado remained in forested areas with severe tree damage.\n|-\n|bgcolor=#{{storm colour|cat2}} | <big>'''EF2'''</big>\n|'''NNW of [[Sedona Airport]]'''\n|[[Coconino County, Arizona|Coconino]]\n|{{Coord|34.981|-111.876|name=Kachina (Oct. 6, EF2)}}\n|1610\n|{{convert|2.77|mi|km|}}\n|Significant tree damage in the area.\n|-\n|bgcolor=#{{storm colour|storm}} | <big>'''EF0'''</big>\n|'''SE of [[Cordes Lakes, Arizona|Cordes Lakes]]'''\n|[[Yavapai County, Arizona|Yavapai]]\n|{{Coord|34.1358|-112.055|name=Cordes Lakes(Oct. 6, EF0)}}\n|1730\n|{{convert|7.26|mi|km|}}\n|Tornado remained over grasslands east of [[Interstate 17]].\n|-\n|bgcolor=#{{storm colour|cat3}} | <big>'''EF3'''</big>\n|'''SE of [[Tuba City, Arizona|Tuba City]]'''\n|[[Coconino County, Arizona|Coconino]]\n|{{Coord|35.9342|-111.001|name=Tuba City (Oct. 6, EF3)}}\n|1905\n|unknown\n|Very large tornado, e